\begin_layout Section
Introduction to Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{module}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 consists of an abelian group on which 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 acts by additive maps: there is a scalar multiplication function 
\begin_inset Formula $R\times M\to M$
\end_inset

 denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,m)\mapsto am$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $1u=u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(bu)=(ab)u$
\end_inset

.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a(u+v)=au+av$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(a+b)u=au+bu$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Throughout these notes, we often write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 without specifying what 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is.
 In either case, it is understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then both 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules with the obvious addition and scalar multiplication operations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-modules are just 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}=\{(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mid x_{i}\in R\}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with component-wise addition and scalar multiplication.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 A map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
module homomorphism 
\series default
(or simply 
\series bold
homomoprhism
\series default
) or 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\series bold
-linear map
\series default
 (or simply linear map) if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(au+bv)=a\varphi(u)+b\varphi(v).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A bijective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism is called an 
\series bold
isomorphism
\series default
.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
isomorphic to
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cong N$
\end_inset

, if there exists an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Submodules, Kernels, and Quotient Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 A nonempty subset 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset M$
\end_inset

 is call a 
\series bold
submodule 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in N$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
au+v\in N.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The next definition gives us two important examples of submodules.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 The 
\series bold
kernel 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ker\varphi:=\{u\in M\mid\varphi(u)=0\}.
\]

\end_inset

The 
\series bold
image 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{im}\,\varphi:=\{\varphi(u)\in N\mid u\in M\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(au+v) & =a\varphi(u)+\varphi(v)\\
 & =a\cdot0+0\\
 & =0+0\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $au+v\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0)\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u),\varphi(v)\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\varphi(u)+\varphi(v) & =\varphi(au)+\varphi(v)\\
 & =\varphi(au+v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\varphi(u)+\varphi(v)\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module and 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset M$
\end_inset

 be a submodule.
 We define the 
\series bold
quotient
\series default
 
\series bold
module 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $M/N$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M/N=\{m+N\mid m\in M\}.
\]

\end_inset

That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $M/N$
\end_inset

 is the set of equivalence classes of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\in M$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if 
\begin_inset Formula $m-n\in N$
\end_inset

.
 An equivalent class is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $m+N$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Each element in the class 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{m}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
representative 
\series default
of the class.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism.
 Then the 
\series bold
cokernel 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Coker}\varphi=N/\mbox{Im}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Translating Modules Between Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Restriction of scalars functor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module, then we can restrict it to an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 has the same underlying abelian group structure as 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 but with scalar multiplication given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot v=f(a)v
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N$
\end_inset

.
 This is called 
\series bold
restriction of scalars 
\series default
since in the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq S$
\end_inset

 we are just restricting the 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-action to an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-action.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon N\to N'$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module linear map, then we define an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}\colon N_{R}\to N'_{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{R}(v)=\psi(v)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}$
\end_inset

 is indeed an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 We just need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}$
\end_inset

 respects scalar multiplication since additivity is clear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{R}(a\cdot v) & =\psi_{R}(f(a)v)\\
 & =\psi(f(a)v)\\
 & =f(a)\psi(v)\\
 & =a\cdot\psi(v)\\
 & =a\cdot\psi_{R}(v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module linear map.
 It is easy to check that we obtain a functor
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-_{R}\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{S}\to\mathbf{Mod}_{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extension of scalars functor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, then we can extend it to an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $S\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 where scalar multiplication is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot(b\otimes u)=ab\otimes u
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 This is called 
\series bold
extension of scalars
\series default
 since in the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq S$
\end_inset

 we are just extending the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-action to an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-action.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to M'$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module linear map, then we define an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $1\otimes\varphi\colon S\otimes_{R}M\to S\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 on elementary tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $a\otimes u\in S\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1\otimes\varphi)(a\otimes u)=a\otimes\varphi(u),
\]

\end_inset

and then extend this linearly everywhere else.
 We just need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\otimes\varphi$
\end_inset

 respects scalar multiplication since additivity is clear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in S$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b\otimes u$
\end_inset

 be an elementary tensor in 
\begin_inset Formula $S\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(1\otimes\varphi)(a\cdot(b\otimes u)) & =(1\otimes\varphi)(ab\otimes u)\\
 & =ab\otimes\varphi(u)\\
 & =a\cdot(b\otimes\varphi(u))\\
 & =a\cdot((1\otimes\varphi)(b\otimes u)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\otimes\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module linear map.
 It is easy to check that we obtain a functor
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\otimes_{R}-\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{R}\to\mathbf{Mod}_{S}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Restricting scalars and extending scalars form an adjoint pair
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functors 
\begin_inset Formula $-_{R}\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{S}\to\mathbf{Mod}_{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{R}S\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{R}\mapsto\mathbf{Mod}_{S}$
\end_inset

 are adjoint functors.
 In a formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N_{R})\cong\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(M\otimes_{R}S,N).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let us calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(R\slash I,R\slash I)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(R\slash I,R\slash I) & \cong\mathrm{Hom}_{R\slash I}((R\slash I)\otimes_{R}(R\slash I),R\slash I)\\
 & \cong\mathrm{Hom}_{R\slash I}(R\slash I,R\slash I)\\
 & \cong R\slash I.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Base Change
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another type of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module that can be viewed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module.
 For simplicity, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subset S$
\end_inset

 is an extension of rings.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module.
 Through restriction of scalars, we can view 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Thus we can consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module via the action
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\cdot\varphi(v)=\varphi(bv)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subset S$
\end_inset

 be a ring extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(N,N')$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,M')$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M,M'$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $N,N'$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N',M)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{*}\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M')$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Translated Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we want to discuss how to translate an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{x}:=\left\{ y+x\mid y\in M\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We define addition and scaling operations as follows.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and, 
\begin_inset Formula $y+x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'+x$
\end_inset

 are two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(y+x)\dot{+}(y'+x)=y+y'+x
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot(y+x)=a\cdot y+x.
\]

\end_inset

Addition 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{+}$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{x}$
\end_inset

 into an abelian group with identity being 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and one can check that all of the conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{x}$
\end_inset

 to be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module are satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We can generalize the above constrution as follows: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to some set 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

.
 We define addition and scaling operations as follows: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\dot{+}y=\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot x=\varphi\left(a\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Addition 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{+}$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 into an abelian group with identity being 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0)$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, we have associativity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(x\dot{+}y\right)\dot{+}z & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\dot{+}z\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}\left(\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\right)\dot{+}\varphi^{-1}\left(z\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\dot{+}\varphi^{-1}\left(z\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\left(\varphi^{-1}(y)\dot{+}\varphi^{-1}\left(z\right)\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}\left(\varphi^{-1}(y)\dot{+}\varphi^{-1}\left(z\right)\right)\right)\right)\\
 & =x\dot{+}\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(y)+\varphi^{-1}(z)\right)\\
 & =x\dot{+}\left(y\dot{+}z\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and we have commutativity: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x\dot{+}y & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(y)+\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)\\
 & =y\dot{+}x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can check that all of the conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 to be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module are satisfied.
 For instance, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\cdot\left(x\dot{+}y\right) & =a\cdot\left(\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\left(\varphi^{-1}\left(\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\right)\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\varphi^{-1}(x)+a\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(a\cdot x)+\varphi^{-1}(a\cdot y)\right)\\
 & =a\cdot x\dot{+}a\cdot y.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(a+b)\cdot x & =\varphi\left((a+b)\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\varphi^{-1}(x)+b\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(a\cdot x)+\varphi^{-1}(b\cdot x)\right)\\
 & =a\cdot x\dot{+}b\cdot x
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(ab)\cdot x & =\varphi\left(ab\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\varphi^{-1}\left(\varphi(b\varphi^{-1}(x))\right)\right)\\
 & =a\cdot(\varphi(b\varphi^{-1}(x)))\\
 & =a\cdot(b\cdot x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The way we defined addition and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-scaling on 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(ax+by) & =\varphi(\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(ax))+\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(by)))\\
 & =\varphi(ax)\dot{+}\varphi(by)\\
 & =\varphi(a\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(x)))\dot{+}\varphi(b\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(y)))\\
 & =a\cdot\varphi(x)\dot{+}b\cdot\varphi(y)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}=M$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 be additive, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x+y)=\varphi(x)+\varphi(y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{+}$
\end_inset

 is the same 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is additive and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x\dot{+}y & =\varphi(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y))\\
 & =\varphi(\varphi^{-1}(x+y))\\
 & =x+y
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, we can still have a different scaling map, as long as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is not 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-linear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Free Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Free Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{n}\in M$
\end_inset

.
 We say the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{1},\dots,u_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if the following conditions hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it generates 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module: for each 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=a_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}u_{n},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it is linearly independent: if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}u_{n}=0,
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

} be a collection of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 indexed over some (possibly infinite) set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 We say the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it generates 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module: for each 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\lambda_{1}},\dots,u_{\lambda_{n}}\in\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda_{1}},\dots,a_{\lambda_{n}}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=a_{\lambda_{1}}u_{\lambda_{1}}+\cdots+a_{\lambda_{n}}u_{\lambda_{n}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
every finite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent: if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda_{1}},\dots,a_{\lambda_{n}}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{\lambda_{1}}u_{\lambda_{1}}+\cdots+a_{\lambda_{n}}u_{\lambda_{n}}=0,
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda_{i}}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\series default
if it has a basis.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
standard free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 It has as basis the 
\series bold
standard basis elements 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th entry and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 everywhere else.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is not a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in R$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $r\overline{s}=\overline{rs}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\series bold
torsion
\series default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 makes linear independence fail for elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 when taking coefficients from 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Universal Mapping Property of Free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Free modules are characterized by the following universal mapping property:
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 indexed over a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}\subseteq M$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon F\to M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e_{\lambda})=u_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of diagrams, this is pictured as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
{ e_{ 
\backslash
lambda } 
\backslash
} 
\backslash
arrow[r,hookrightarrow] 
\backslash
arrow[dr, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

e_{
\backslash
lambda } 
\backslash
mapsto u_{
\backslash
lambda } 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

,swap] & F 
\backslash
arrow[d, dashed, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
exists ! 
\backslash
varphi 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

& M   
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the universal mapping property of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, let us prove the following theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremuniversalmappingoffreemodules}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are finite rank free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 respectively, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\cong G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By the universal mapping property of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon F\to G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e_{i})=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon G\to F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(f_{i})=e_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\varphi\colon F\to F$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi\circ\varphi)(e_{i})=e_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 But we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $1(e_{i})=e_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\colon F\to F$
\end_inset

 is the identity map.
 Therefore by uniqueness of the map in the universal mapping property of
 free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\varphi=1$
\end_inset

.
 A similar argument shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\psi=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\in F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\cong R^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that you can prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremuniversalmappingoffreemodules})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 without the universal mapping property of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, but the point is that you'd have to show well-definedness, linearity,
 etc...
 of the maps constructed.
 The point is that all of this is built into the universal mapping property
 of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Representing 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module Homomorphisms By Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\{\gamma_{1},\dots,\gamma_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in F$
\end_inset

, then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

, there exists unique 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\beta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined, we are justified in making the following definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
column representation of 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to the basis
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[v]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[v]_{\beta}:=\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propcolumnislinear}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}\colon V\to R^{m}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}(v)=[v]_{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2}\in V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

, there exists unique 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i1},a_{i2}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i1}\beta_{i}\quad\text{and}\quad v_{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i2}\beta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

 Therefore we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{1}v_{1}+a_{2}v_{2} & =a_{1}\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i1}\beta_{i}+a_{2}\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i2}\beta_{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}(a_{1}a_{i1}+a_{2}a_{i2})\beta_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[a_{1}v_{1}+a_{2}v_{2}]_{\beta} & =\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}a_{11}+a_{2}a_{12}\\
\vdots\\
a_{1}a_{m1}+a_{2}a_{m2}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =a_{1}\begin{pmatrix}a_{11}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m1}
\end{pmatrix}+a_{2}\begin{pmatrix}a_{12}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m2}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =a_{1}[v_{1}]_{\beta}+a_{2}[v_{2}]_{\beta}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\beta_{i}]=e_{i}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the column vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and whose entry everywhere else is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 restricts to a bijection on basis sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}\colon\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{m}\}\to\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\},
\]

\end_inset

and so it must be an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Matrix Representation of a Linear Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

, there exists unique elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi(\beta_{i})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{ji}\gamma_{j}\label{eq:matrixrepeq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined, we are justified in making the following definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
matrix representation of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to the bases
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
and
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[\varphi]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\varphi]_{\beta}^{\gamma}:=\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propcommutative}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 be a linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\varphi]_{\beta}^{\gamma}[v]_{\beta}=[\varphi(v)]_{\gamma}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In terms of diagrams, this proposition says that the following diagram
 is commutative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} R^m 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
text{[}
\backslash
varphi 
\backslash
text{]}^{
\backslash
gamma }_{
\backslash
beta } 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & R^n  
\backslash

\backslash
 F 
\backslash
arrow[u, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 
\backslash
text{[} 
\backslash
cdot  
\backslash
text{]} _{
\backslash
beta } 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
varphi 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, swap]  & G  
\backslash
arrow[u, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 
\backslash
text{[} 
\backslash
cdot 
\backslash
text{]} _{
\backslash
gamma } 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap]    
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Submodules, Kernels, and Quotient Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 A non-empty subset 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset M$
\end_inset

 is call a 
\series bold
submodule 
\series default
of of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
am+n\in N.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The next definition gives us two important examples of submodules.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism.
 The 
\series bold
kernel 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=\{m\in M\mid\varphi(m)=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
image 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Im}\varphi=\{\varphi(m)\mid m\in M\}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Im}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module and 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset M$
\end_inset

 be a submodule.
 We define the 
\series bold
quotient
\series default
 
\series bold
module 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $M/N$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M/N=\{m+N\mid m\in M\}.
\]

\end_inset

That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $M/N$
\end_inset

 is the set of equivalence classes of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\in M$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if 
\begin_inset Formula $m-n\in N$
\end_inset

.
 An equivalent class is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $m+N$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Each element in the class 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{m}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
representative 
\series default
of the class.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism.
 Then the 
\series bold
cokernel 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Coker}\varphi=N/\mbox{Im}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is called of 
\series bold
finite presentation
\series default
 or 
\series bold
finitely presented 
\series default
if there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

-matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to the cokernel of the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A^{m}\to A^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
presentation matrix 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  A^m 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
varphi "] & A^n 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
to denote a presentation of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Constructive module theory is concerned with modules of finite presentation,
 that is, with modules which can be given as the cokernel of some matrix.
 All operations with modules are then represented by operations with the
 corresponding presentation matrices.
 We shall see later on that every finitely generated module over a Noetherian
 ring is finitely presented.
 As polynomial rings and localizations thereof are Noetherian every finitely
 generated module over these rings is of finite presentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Q}[x,y,z]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be the submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}$
\end_inset

 generated by the column vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $(xy,yz)^{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(xz,z^{2})^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 This means we have a map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=huge, row sep=0.4, ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] A^2 
\backslash
arrow{r}{ 
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} xy & xz 
\backslash

\backslash
 yz & z^2 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& M 
\backslash

\backslash
 e_1 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto,shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& xye_1 + yze_2 
\backslash

\backslash
 e_2 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto, shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& xze_1 + z^2 e_2 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain a presentation of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, we need to compute the kernel of this map.
 The kernel is generated by the column vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(-z,y)^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $(-z,y)^{t}$
\end_inset

 is the presentation matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=huge, row sep=0.4, ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] A 
\backslash
arrow{r}{
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} -z 
\backslash

\backslash
 y 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& A^2 
\backslash
arrow{r}{ 
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} xy & xz 
\backslash

\backslash
 yz & z^2 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& M 
\backslash

\backslash
 e_1 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto,shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& -ze_1 + ye_2 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
& e_1 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto,shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& xye_1 + yze_2 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
& e_2 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto, shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& xze_1 + z^2 e_2 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{modulehomomorphism}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules with presentations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  A^m 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
varphi "] & A^n 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
pi "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
quad 
\backslash
mbox{and} 
\backslash
quad 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  A^r 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
psi "] & A^s 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
kappa "] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0.
 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism, then there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:A^{m}\to A^{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta:A^{n}\to A^{s}$
\end_inset

 such that the following diagram commutes: 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  A^m 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
varphi "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, " 
\backslash
alpha "] & A^n 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
pi "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, " 
\backslash
beta "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
arrow[d, " 
\backslash
lambda "] & 0 
\backslash

\backslash
  A^r 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
psi "] & A^s 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
kappa "] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0.
 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\circ\varphi=\psi\circ\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\circ\pi=\kappa\circ\beta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta:A^{n}\to A^{s}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\mbox{Im}(\varphi))\subset\mbox{Im}(\psi).$
\end_inset

 Then there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:A^{m}\to A^{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda:M\to N$
\end_inset

 such that the corresponding diagram commutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1):$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n}$
\end_inset

 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in A^{s}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x_{i})=(\lambda\circ\pi)(e_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}e_{i})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\circ\pi=\kappa\circ\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\kappa\circ\beta\circ\varphi)(f_{i})=(\lambda\circ\pi\circ\varphi)(f_{i})=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\varphi(f_{i}))\in\mbox{Ker}(\kappa)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in A^{r}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(y_{i})=(\beta\circ\varphi)(f_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\sum_{i=1}^{n}b_{n}f_{i})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}b_{i}y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Again 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\alpha=\beta\circ\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(2):$
\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(m)=(\kappa\circ\beta)(\tilde{m})$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{m}\in A^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\tilde{m})=m$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this definition does not depend on the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{m}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{m}+\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

 be another lift where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\kappa\circ\beta)(\tilde{m}+\varphi(x))=(\kappa\circ\beta)(\tilde{m})+(\kappa\circ\beta\circ\varphi)(x)=(\kappa\circ\beta)(\tilde{m})$
\end_inset

.
 Obviously, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\circ\pi=\kappa\circ\beta$
\end_inset

.
 We can define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as in 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Short Exact Sequences and Splitting Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


