end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Functorial Properties of Hom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Covariant Functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,-)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We obtain a covariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,-)\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{R}\to\mathbf{Mod}_{R}
\]

\end_inset

from the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules to itself, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is assigned to the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

 and where the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon N\to N'$
\end_inset

 is assigned to the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{*}\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N')$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{*}(\psi)=\varphi\psi
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,-)$
\end_inset

 preserves compositions and identities.
 We first check that it preserves compositions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon N\to N'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi'\colon M'\to N''$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear maps and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi'\varphi)_{*}(\psi) & =\varphi'\varphi\psi\\
 & =\varphi'_{*}(\varphi\psi)\\
 & =\varphi'_{*}(\varphi_{*}(\psi))\\
 & =(\varphi'_{*}\varphi_{*})(\psi)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi'\varphi)_{*}=\varphi'_{*}\varphi_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,-)$
\end_inset

 preserves compositions.
 Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,-)$
\end_inset

 preserves identities.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(1_{N})_{*}(\psi) & =1_{N}\psi\\
 & =\psi\\
 & =1_{\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)}(\psi).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1_{N})_{*}=1_{\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,-)$
\end_inset

 preserves identities.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Contravariant Functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,N)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We obtain a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,N)\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{R}\to\mathbf{Mod}_{R}
\]

\end_inset

from the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules to itself, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is assigned to the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

 and where the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to M'$
\end_inset

 is assigned to the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M',N)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(\psi')=\psi'\varphi
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M',N)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,N)$
\end_inset

 preserves compositions and identities.
 We first check that it preserves compositions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to M'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi'\colon M'\to M''$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear maps and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi''\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M'',N)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi'\varphi)^{*}(\psi'') & =\psi''\varphi'\varphi\\
 & =(\varphi'^{*}(\psi''))\varphi\\
 & =\varphi^{*}(\varphi'^{*}(\psi''))\\
 & =(\varphi^{*}\varphi'^{*})(\psi'')
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi'\varphi)^{*}=(\varphi^{*}\varphi'^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,N)$
\end_inset

 preserves compositions.
 Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,N)$
\end_inset

 preserves identities.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(1_{M})^{*}(\psi) & =\psi1_{M}\\
 & =\psi\\
 & =1_{\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)}(\psi).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1_{M})^{*}=1_{\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,N)$
\end_inset

 preserves identities.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Left Exactness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-N)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{contravarianthomleftexact1}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  M_1 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _1 "] & M_2  
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _2 "] & M_3  
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0     
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact if and only if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 the induced sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{contravarianthomleftexact2}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M_3 ,N) 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
varphi _2 ^* "] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M_2 ,N) 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
varphi _1 ^* "] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M_1 ,N)  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{contravarianthomleftexact1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is exact and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be any 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We first show exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M_{3},N)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}\in\ker\varphi_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\varphi_{2}^{*}(\psi_{3})\\
 & =\psi_{3}\varphi_{2}\\
 & =\psi_{3},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is surjective to obtain the third line from the second line.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective, which implies exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M_{3},N)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M_{2},N)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}\in\ker\varphi_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\varphi_{1}^{*}(\psi_{2})\\
 & =\psi_{2}\varphi_{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 kills the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}\colon M_{3}\to N$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in M_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

 (such a choice is possible since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is surjective).
 We define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{3}(u_{3})=\psi_{2}(u_{2}).
\]

\end_inset

The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 kills the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 was another lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v_{2}-u_{2} & \in\ker\varphi_{2}\\
 & =\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{2}(v_{2}) & =\psi_{2}(v_{2}-u_{2}+u_{2})\\
 & =\psi_{2}(v_{2}-u_{2})+\psi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =\psi_{2}(u_{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3},v_{3}\in M_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose lifts of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3},v_{3}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2},v_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(v_{2})=v_{3}$
\end_inset

).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $au_{2}+bv_{2}$
\end_inset

 is easily seen to be a lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $au_{3}+bv_{3}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and so we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{3}(au_{3}+bv_{3}) & =\psi_{2}(au_{2}+bv_{2})\\
 & =a\psi_{2}(u_{2})+b\psi_{2}(v_{2})\\
 & =a\psi_{3}(u_{3})+b\psi_{3}(v_{3}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear.
 Finally, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{2}^{*}(\psi_{3})(u_{2}) & =(\psi_{3}\varphi_{2})(u_{2})\\
 & =\psi_{3}(\varphi_{2}(u_{2}))\\
 & =\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =\psi_{2}(u_{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}=\varphi_{2}^{*}(\psi_{3})$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we have exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M_{2},N)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{contravarianthomleftexact1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is exact for all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 We first show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $N=M_{3}\slash\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon M_{3}\to M_{3}\slash\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the quotient map.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{2}^{*}(\pi) & =\pi\varphi_{2}\\
 & =0\\
 & =\varphi_{2}^{*}(0).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows from injectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{3}=\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 First set 
\begin_inset Formula $N=M_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then exactness of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{contravarianthomleftexact1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =(\varphi_{1}^{*}\varphi_{2}^{*})(1_{M_{3}})\\
 & =(\varphi_{1}^{*}(\varphi_{2}^{*}(1_{M_{3}}))\\
 & =\varphi_{1}^{*}(1_{M_{3}}\varphi_{2})\\
 & =1_{M_{3}}\varphi_{2}\varphi_{1}\\
 & =\varphi_{2}\varphi_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi_{2}\supseteq\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, set 
\begin_inset Formula $N=M_{2}\slash\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon M_{2}\to M_{2}\slash\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the quotient map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}^{*}(\pi) & =\pi\varphi_{1}\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}\colon M_{3}\to M_{2}\slash\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=\varphi_{2}^{*}(\psi_{3})$
\end_inset

 by exactness of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{contravarianthomleftexact1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in\ker\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\psi_{3}(0)\\
 & =\psi_{3}(\varphi_{2}(u_{2}))\\
 & =(\psi_{3}\varphi_{2})(u_{2})\\
 & =(\varphi_{2}^{*}(\psi_{3}))(u_{2})\\
 & =\pi(u_{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi_{2}\subseteq\mathrm{im}\,\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Naturality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propfunctorialpropertiesnaturality}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to M'$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Then we obtain an induced natural transformation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(\varphi,-)\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,-)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M',-)
\]

\end_inset

between functors.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon N\to N'$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 We need to check that the following diagram commutes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{naturalcommutehom}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}  _R (M,N )  
\backslash
arrow[d, swap, "
\backslash
psi _*  "]       
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\backslash
varphi ^* 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}  _R (M', N ) 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
psi _* "] 
\backslash

\backslash
  
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}  _R (M,N' )      
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\backslash
varphi ^* 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}  _R (M',N' ) 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\psi_{*}\varphi^{*})(\phi) & =\psi_{*}(\varphi^{*}(\phi))\\
 & =\psi_{*}(\phi\varphi)\\
 & =\psi\phi\varphi\\
 & =\varphi^{*}(\psi\phi)\\
 & =\varphi^{*}(\psi_{*}(\phi))\\
 & =(\varphi^{*}\psi_{*})(\phi).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{*}\varphi^{*}=\varphi^{*}\psi_{*}$
\end_inset

, and so the diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{naturalcommutehom})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 commutes.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By a similar argument, every 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon N\to N'$
\end_inset

 induces a natural transformation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,\psi)\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,N)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,N').
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Nakayama's Lemma and its Consequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nakayama's Lemma is a powerful tool we use in Commutative Algebra.
 In order to know Commutative Algebra, one must be familiar with Nakayama's
 Lemma.
 Before we state and prove Nakayama's Lemma, we need to discuss the Jacobson
 radical of a ring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
Jacobson radical 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rad}(R)$
\end_inset

, is defined by the formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{rad}(R):=\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{m}\subset R\\
\mathfrak{m}\text{ maximal}
}
}\mathfrak{m}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rad}(R)=\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{rad}(R)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $1-x\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $1-x\notin R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a maximal ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $1-x$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 to be this maximal ideal.
 But then this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, contradicting the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{rad}(R)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nakayama's Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now state and prove Nakayama's Lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmanakayama}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Nakayama).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rad}(R)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset M$
\end_inset

 a submodule such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M=IM+N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M=N$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $M=IM$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $M\neq N$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{s}\in M$
\end_inset

 such that their classes form a system of generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash N$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is minimal.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u_{s} & \in M\\
 & =IM+N,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{s}\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{s}=\sum_{r=1}^{s}x_{r}u_{r}+v.
\]

\end_inset

This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-x_{s})u_{s}=\sum_{r=1}^{s-1}x_{r}u_{r}+v.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}$
\end_inset

 is contained in every maximal ideal, 
\begin_inset Formula $1-x_{s}$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{s}=\sum_{r=1}^{s-1}x_{r}(1-x_{s})^{-1}u_{r}+(1-x_{s})^{-1}v,
\]

\end_inset

which contradicts the minimality of the chosen system of generators.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 be a local ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{s}$
\end_inset

 be elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that their classes form a system of generators for the 
\begin_inset Formula $(R\slash\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

-vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{s}$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}_{1},\dots,\overline{u}_{s}$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $(R\slash\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

-vector space, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M=\mathfrak{m}M+Ru_{1}+\cdots+Ru_{s}.\label{eq:Msumgen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{s}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{u}=a_{1}\overline{u}_{1}+\cdots+a_{s}\overline{u}_{s}.
\]

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u-(a_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{s}u_{s})\in\mathfrak{m}M.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u & =u-(a_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{s}u_{s})+(a_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{s}u_{s})\\
 & \in\mathfrak{m}M+Ru_{1}+\cdots+Ru_{s}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:Msumgen})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with Nakayama's Lemma, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=Ru_{1}+\cdots+Ru_{s}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The finite generation hypothesis is crucial.
 For a counterexample, consider the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}$
\end_inset

 and the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=pR$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M\slash\mathfrak{m}M & =M\slash pM\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $px$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 However, obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $M\neq0$
\end_inset

 (and also 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is not finitely generated as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module in this case).
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K[x,y,z]_{\langle x,y,z\rangle}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle x,y,z\rangle$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with presentation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

R^2 
\backslash
arrow{rrr}{ 
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} 0 & y 
\backslash

\backslash
 xy-1 & xz 
\backslash

\backslash
 xy+1 & xz 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
& R^3 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
& M 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
& 0.
 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\in M$
\end_inset

 be the image the standard basis element 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\in R^{3}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{1},u_{2},u_{3}\}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
a minimal generating set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{R}(R\slash\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 is right-exact, we obtain a presentation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $(R\slash\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

-vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(R/
\backslash
mathfrak{m})^2 
\backslash
arrow{rrr}{ 
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 
\backslash

\backslash
 -1 & 0 
\backslash

\backslash
 1 & 0 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
& (R/
\backslash
mathfrak{m})^3 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
& M / 
\backslash
mathfrak{m} M 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
& 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This presentation matrix has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 In fact, it's not hard to see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M\slash\mathfrak{m}M=K\overline{u}_{1}+K\overline{u}_{3},
\]

\end_inset

since the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $-\overline{u}_{2}+\overline{u}_{3}=0$
\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is superfluous.
 According to Nakayama's Lemma, we should be able to lift 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}_{1},\overline{u}_{3}\in M/\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

 to a minimal generating set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{1},u_{3}\}$
\end_inset

 should be a minimal generating set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 To see that it is, we use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy-1$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to perform the following sequence of elementary row and column operations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}0 & y\\
xy-1 & xz\\
xy+1 & xz
\end{pmatrix}\longrightarrow\begin{pmatrix}0 & y\\
xy-1 & xz\\
0 & \frac{-2xz}{xy-1}
\end{pmatrix}\longrightarrow\begin{pmatrix}0 & y\\
xy-1 & 0\\
0 & \frac{-2xz}{xy-1}
\end{pmatrix}\longrightarrow\begin{pmatrix}0 & y\\
1 & 0\\
0 & \frac{-2xz}{xy-1}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1}',e_{2}'\}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

, then this sequence of elementary row operations corresponds base changes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{e_{1},e_{2},e_{3}\}\to\left\{ e_{1},(xy-1)e_{2}+(xy+1)e_{3},e_{3}\right\} \qquad\text{and}\qquad\{e_{1}',e_{2}'\}\to\left\{ e_{1}',\frac{-xz}{xy-1}e_{1}'+e_{2}'\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}0 & y\\
1 & 0\\
0 & \frac{-2xz}{xy-1}
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be used as a presentation matrix for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Again, the trivial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 implies that we can toss 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 out, so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=Ru_{1}+Ru_{3}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Krull's Intersection Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now prove the following important corollary of Nakayama's Lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Krull's interesection theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal contained in the Jacobson radical of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcap_{k\in\mathbb{N}}I^{k}M=0.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N:=\bigcap_{k}I^{k}M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module since it is a submodule of the finitely generated module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 over the Noetherian ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 By Nakayama's Lemma, it is sufficient to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $IN=N$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}:=\left\{ L\subset M\text{ submodule }\mid L\cap N=IN\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $IN\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 has a maximal element, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 to be such a maximal element.
 It remains to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{k}M\subset L$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, because this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
N & =I^{k}M\cap N\\
 & \subset L\cap N\\
 & =IN,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and from Nakayama's Lemma, we would conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated, it suffices to prove that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 there is some positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}M\subset L$
\end_inset

 (If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{s}\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{r}^{n_{r}}M\subset L$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq r\leq s$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{n_{1}+\cdots+n_{s}}M\subset L$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and consider the chain of ideals 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L:_{M}x\subset L:_{M}x^{2}\subset\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

This chain stabilizes because 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $L:_{M}x^{n}=L:_{M}x^{n+1}.$
\end_inset

 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}M\subset L$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, by the maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 it is enough to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $(L+x^{n}M)\cap N\subset IN$
\end_inset

 since obviously,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
IN & =L\cap N\\
 & \subset(L+x^{n}M)\cap N.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in(L+x^{n}M)\cap N$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v+x^{n}w$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Now
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{n+1}w & =xu-xv\\
 & \in IN+L\\
 & =L\cap N+L\\
 & =L,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in L:_{M}x^{n+1}=L:_{M}x^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}w\in L$
\end_inset

, and, consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in L$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in L\cap N=IN$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Filtrations, Blowups, and the Lemma of Artin-Rees
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Our aim in this subsection is to state and prove the Artin-Rees Lemma.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Filtrations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 of submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
filtration of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M=M_{0}\supset M_{1}\supset M_{2}\supset\cdots$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $QM_{n}\subset M_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
stable 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $QM_{n}=M_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for all sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{Q}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtrations of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and set 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}:=Q^{n}M$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{M_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We define a relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{Q}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtrations of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})\sim(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

 if there exists a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{n+k}\subset M_{n}'\quad\text{and}\quad M'_{n+k}\subset M_{n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
 Indeed, reflexivity and symmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 are clear.
 To see transitivity also holds, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})\sim(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}')\sim(M_{n}'')$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+k}\subset M_{n}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+k}'\subset M_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

, and choose a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+m}'\subset M_{n}''$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+m}''\subset M_{n}'$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M_{n+k+m} & \subset M'_{n+m}\\
 & \subset M''_{n},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and similarly
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M''_{n+k+m} & \subset M'_{n+k}\\
 & \subset M_{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}'')\sim(M_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})\sim(Q^{n}M)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

 is another stable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})\sim(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+k}=Q^{n}M_{k}$
\end_inset

 (we can do this since 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-stable).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M_{n+k} & =Q^{n}M_{k}\\
 & \subset Q^{n}M
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, as 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $QM_{n}\subset M_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge0$
\end_inset

, which implies, in particular
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Q^{n+k}M & \subset M_{n+k}\\
 & \subset M_{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propinversimageqfiltration}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon N\to M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

 is another 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}')\sim(M_{n})$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}'))\sim(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}))$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a descending chain of submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(M_{0})=N$
\end_inset

.
 Also we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Q\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}) & \subset\varphi^{-1}(QM_{n})\\
 & \subset\varphi^{-1}(M_{n+1})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}'))$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+k}\subset M_{n}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+k}'\subset M_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(M_{n+k})\subset\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(M_{n+k}')\subset\varphi^{-1}(M_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1}(M_{n}'))$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon N\to M$
\end_inset

 induces a well-defined map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{Q}^{\infty}(\varphi)\colon\mathcal{C}_{Q}^{\infty}(M)\to\mathcal{C}_{Q}^{\infty}(N).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Blowups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defnblowup}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
blowup algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R):=R+Qt+Q^{2}t^{2}+Q^{3}t^{3}+\cdots\cong\bigoplus_{n\geq0}Q^{n},
\]

\end_inset

where we view 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as an indeterminate variable which keeps track of the grading: the homogeneous
 component in degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)_{n}:=Q^{n}t^{n},
\]

\end_inset

and where multiplication is uniquely determined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(xt^{m})(yt^{n})=xyt^{m+n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $xt^{m}\in Q^{m}t^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yt^{n}\in Q^{n}t^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
blowup module of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\series default
 is the graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{Q}(M):=M+QMt+Q^{2}Mt^{2}+Q^{3}Mt^{3}+\cdots\cong\bigoplus_{n\geq0}Q^{n}M.
\]

\end_inset


\series default
where the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module action is uniquely determined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(xt^{m})(ut^{n})=xut^{m+n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $xt^{m}\in Q^{m}t^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ut^{n}\in Q^{n}Mt^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propblowupofneotherianisnoetherian}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The blowup algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ideal, say 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\rangle_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the irrelevant ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $Qt\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

 is a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

-ideal, with 
\begin_inset Formula $Qt\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)=\langle f_{1}t,\dots,f_{s}t\rangle_{\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi\colon R[X_{1},\dots,X_{s}]\to\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)
\]

\end_inset

induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(X_{r})=tf_{r}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq r\leq s$
\end_inset

.
 This homomorphism is a surjective ring homomorphism from a Noetherian ring,
 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K[x,y]/\langle y^{2}-x^{3}-x^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\langle\overline{x},\overline{y}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi\colon R[u,v]\to\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)
\]

\end_inset

be the surjective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $u\mapsto\overline{x}t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\mapsto\overline{y}t$
\end_inset

.
 The kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an ideal which is homogeneous in the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ker\varphi=\langle v^{2}-(\overline{x}+1)u^{2},\overline{x}v-\overline{y}u\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to an algebraic subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}\times\mathbb{P}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Artin-Rees Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsubsection, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is finitely-generated.
 We are almost ready to state and prove Artin-Rees Lemma, but before we
 do so, let us give a criterion for stability: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}$
\end_inset

 to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

-module given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{M}:=M+M_{1}t+M_{2}t^{2}+\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

, let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{M}_{n} & :=M+M_{1}t+\cdots+M_{n-1}t^{n-1}+\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)M_{n}t^{n}\\
 & =M+M_{1}t+\cdots+M_{n-1}t^{n-1}+M_{n}t^{n}+QM_{n}t^{n+1}+Q^{2}M_{n}t^{n+2}+\cdots.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}_{n}\subset\overline{M}_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{n=0}^{\infty}\overline{M}_{n}=\overline{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $(\overline{M}_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an ascending sequence whose union is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
label{lemmacritforstab}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Criterion for stability).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}$
\end_inset

 is a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

-module if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-stable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}$
\end_inset

 is finitely-generated.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, and so the ascending sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\overline{M}_{n})$
\end_inset

 of submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}$
\end_inset

 must terminate, say at 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}_{k}=\overline{M}$
\end_inset

 since the union of the ascending sequence is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}$
\end_inset

, and this happens if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+k}=Q^{n}M_{k}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-stable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-stable.
 Then as arged above, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}_{k}=\overline{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose such a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

 and observe that the submodules 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

 are finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 (and hence finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

-modules too).
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{M} & =\overline{M}_{k}\\
 & =M+M_{1}t+\cdots+M_{k-1}t^{k-1}+\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)M_{k}t^{k}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we state and prove Artin-Rees Lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{artinrees}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Artin-Rees Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}\cap N)$
\end_inset

 is a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propinversimageqfiltration})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}\cap N)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 since it is the sequence obtained from the inverse image of the inclusion
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $N\hookrightarrow M$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}\cap N)$
\end_inset

 is stable.
 Appealing to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{lemmacritforstab})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we just need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{N}$
\end_inset

 is a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

-module, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{N}:=N+(M_{1}\cap N)t+(M_{2}\cap N)t^{2}+\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

This is clear though since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{N}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{M}$
\end_inset

 which is finitely-generated, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{Q}(R)$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{N}$
\end_inset

 must be finitely-generated too.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Consequences of Artin-Rees Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with an alternative proof of Krull's Intersection Theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Krull's Interesection Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian local ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M=0.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $N:=\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}Q^{n}M$
\end_inset

.
 By Artin-Rees, the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(N\cap Q^{n}M)$
\end_inset

 is stable.
 Thus there exists a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
QN & =Q\left(N\cap Q^{k}M\right)\\
 & =N\cap Q^{k+1}M\\
 & =N,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and by Nakayama's lemma, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 For any homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon I\to R\slash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, there exists a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 factors through 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\slash(\mathfrak{p}^{d}\cap I)\cong(\mathfrak{p}^{d}+I)\slash\mathfrak{p}^{d}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By Artin-Rees, 
\begin_inset Formula $(I\cap\mathfrak{p}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-filtration.
 Therefore this exists a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap\mathfrak{p}^{d}=\mathfrak{p}\left(I\cap\mathfrak{p}^{d-1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap\mathfrak{p}^{d}\subset\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and let 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M_1 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M_2 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M_3 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
be a short exact sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & B_Q (M_1 ) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & B_Q (M_2 ) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & B_Q (M_3 ) 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-adic Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We now wish to discuss the 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-adic topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The topology is constructed as follow: choose a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset


\series bold
-adic topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is defined to be the topology generated by sets of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{m}(u):=u+M_{m}\label{eq:iadicbasis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that sets of the form 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:iadicbasis})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 form a basis for this topology since they are closed under finite intersections
: if 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq m\geq0$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(u+M_{m})\cap(v+M_{n})=\begin{cases}
v+I^{n}M & \text{if }u-v\in M_{m}\\
\emptyset & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We want to show that the topology just defined does not depend on the choice
 of a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-adic filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, so suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

 is another stable 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+k}\subset M_{n}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n+k}'\subset M_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies that the topologies induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n}')$
\end_inset

 are the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Completion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then the module 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{M}_{(M_{n})}:=\left\{ (\overline{u}_{n})\in\prod_{i=1}^{\infty}M\slash M_{n}\mid u_{n}\equiv u_{m}\text{ mod }M_{m}\text{ if }n>m\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

is called the 
\series bold
completion of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{n})$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Modules of Finite Length
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(M)$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all 
\series bold
chains of submodules 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}(M):=\left\{ \mathcal{M}=\left(M=M_{0}\supset M_{1}\supset\cdots\supset M_{n}=0\right)\mid M_{i}\neq M_{i+1}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\left(M=M_{0}\supset M_{1}\supset\cdots\supset M_{n}=0\right)\in\mathcal{C}(M)$
\end_inset

, then 
\series bold
length
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{M}\right):=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(M)<\infty$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Artinian
\series default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Artinian as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
Artinian ring
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(M)$
\end_inset

 forms a poset in the following way: Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M},\mathcal{M}'\in\mathcal{C}(M)$
\end_inset

, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}'\geq\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 if we can obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 by removing some submodules in the chain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}:=\left(M=M_{0}\supset M_{1}\supset\cdots\supset M_{n}=0\right)$
\end_inset

 a chain of submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
composition series 
\series default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero simple module for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define the 
\series bold
length 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(M)$
\end_inset

, to be the least length of a composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is not a composition series, then there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 is not simple.
 Thus, there exists a nonzero proper submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $M'/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}'$
\end_inset

 be the chain of submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}'=\left(M=M_{0}\cdots\supset M_{i}\supset M'\supset M_{i+1}\supset\cdots\supset M_{n}=0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}'\geq\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(\mathcal{M}')=\text{length}(\mathcal{M})+1.$
\end_inset

 So a composition series must be maximal with respect to the partial order.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A simple module must be generated by any nonzero element.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a composition series, then each 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}\cong A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for some maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, which may be described by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\text{Ann}\left(M_{i}/M_{i+1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremlength}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a finite composition series if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Artinian and Noetherian.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a finite composition series 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}:=\left(M=M_{0}\supset M_{1}\supset\cdots\supset M_{n}=0\right)$
\end_inset

 of length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every chain of submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has length less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and can be refined to a composition series.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sum of the localization maps 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 a prime ideal, gives an isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M\cong\bigoplus_{\mathfrak{p}}M_{\mathfrak{p}},
\]

\end_inset

where the sum is taken over all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such that some 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}\cong A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The number of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-module, and is thus independent of the composition series chosen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $M=M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is annihilated by some power of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Artinian and Noetherian, so that it satisfies both ascending chain condition
 and descending chain condition on submodules.
 By the ascending chain condition we may choose a maximal proper submodule
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

, a maximal proper submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

, and so on.
 By the descending chain condition this sequence of submodules must terminate,
 and it can only terminate when some 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $M=M_{0}\supset M_{1}\supset\cdots\supset M_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 is a compostion series for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset M$
\end_inset

 is a proper submodule.
 We shall show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(N)<\text{length}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 The idea is simple: We intersect the terms of the given composition series
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and derive a shorter composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 The quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $(N\cap M_{i})/(N\cap M_{i+1})$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(N\cap M_{i}+M_{i+1})/M_{i+1}\subset M_{i}/M_{i+1}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 is simple, we have either 
\begin_inset Formula $(N\cap M_{i})/(N\cap M_{i+1})=0$
\end_inset

 or else 
\begin_inset Formula $(N\cap M_{i})/(N\cap M_{i+1})$
\end_inset

 is simple and 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap M_{i}+M_{i+1}=M_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the latter possibility cannot happen for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming on the contrary that it did, we prove by descending induction
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $N\supset M_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and we get a contradiction from the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $N\supset M_{0}=M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $i=n$
\end_inset

, then clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $N\supset M_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Supposing by induction that 
\begin_inset Formula $N\supset M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap M_{i}=N\cap M_{i}+M_{i+1}=M_{i}$
\end_inset

, and it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $N\supset M_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 From these facts, we see that the sequence of submodules
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N\supset N\cap M_{1}\supset\cdots\supset N\cap M_{n}=0
\]

\end_inset

can be changed, by leaving out the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap M_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap M_{i}=N\cap M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

, to a composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 whose length is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Since we could do this for any composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{length}(N)<\text{length}(M).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose now that 
\begin_inset Formula $M=N_{0}\supset N_{1}\supset\cdots\supset N_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a chain of submodules.
 We shall show by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(M)$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq\text{length}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 This is obvious if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(M)=0$
\end_inset

, since then 
\begin_inset Formula $M=0$
\end_inset

.
 By the argument above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(N_{1})<\text{length}(M)$
\end_inset

; so by induction, the length of the chain 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}\supset\cdots\supset N_{k}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1\leq\text{length}(N_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(N_{1})<\text{length}(M)$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq\text{length}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 From the definition of length, it now follows that every maximal chain
 of submodules has length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and every chain of submodules can be refined to a maximal chain.
 Further, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a uniform bound on the lengths of all ascending or descending chains
 of submodules, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has both ascending chain condition and descending chain condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It suffices to show that the given map becomes an isomorphism after localizing
 at any maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This will be easy once we understand what happens when we localize a module
 of finite length.
 We begin with the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has length 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, that is, when 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a simple module.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cong A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for some maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\text{Ann}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

, then since 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is a field, the elements outside of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 acts as units on 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

, and we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A/\mathfrak{q})_{\mathfrak{q}}=A/\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 If on the other hand 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\neq\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

, then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is maximal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\subset\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{\mathfrak{q}}=A_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{q}}=A_{\mathfrak{q}}/\mathfrak{p}_{\mathfrak{q}}=0.
\]

\end_inset

It follows in particular from this that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

 are distinct prime ideals, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{\mathfrak{q}})_{\mathfrak{q}'}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We now return to the general case, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(M)=n<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 localizes to a sequence of submodules 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{\mathfrak{q}}=(M_{0})_{\mathfrak{q}}\supset(M_{1})_{\mathfrak{q}}\supset\cdots\supset(M_{n})_{\mathfrak{q}}=0.
\]

\end_inset

The modules 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 have length 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, so the case already treated shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{i}/M_{i+1})_{\mathfrak{q}}=M_{i}/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\text{Ann}\left(M_{i}/M_{i+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{i}/M_{i+1})_{\mathfrak{q}}=0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

 has a finite composition series corresponding to the subseries of the one
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, obtained by keeping only those 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{i})_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}\cong A/\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if none of the modules 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{q}}=0$
\end_inset

; and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

 are distinct maximal ideals, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{\mathfrak{q}})_{\mathfrak{q}'}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Now consider the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha:M\to\bigoplus_{\mathfrak{p}}M_{\mathfrak{p}},
\]

\end_inset

where the sum is taken over all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such that some 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}\cong A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 We see from the above that we could harmlessly extend the sum to all maximal
 ideals; the new terms are all 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 For any maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and any module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{\mathfrak{q}})_{\mathfrak{q}}=M_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

, so the identity map is one part of the localization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{\mathfrak{q}}:M_{\mathfrak{q}}\to\left(\bigoplus_{\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Max}(A)}M_{\mathfrak{p}}\right)_{\mathfrak{q}}=\bigoplus_{\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Max}(A)}\left(M_{\mathfrak{p}}\right)_{\mathfrak{q}}.
\]

\end_inset

But if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\neq\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has finite length, then we have seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{\mathfrak{p}})_{\mathfrak{q}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

 is the identity map for every maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

, and it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an isomorpism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is annihilated by a power of a maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\neq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is another maximal ideal, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 contains an element not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 This element acts as a unit on 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, by part 2, 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cong M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cong M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 The preceeding description of localization shows that every factor 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}\cong A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 By induction, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}^{d}M\subset M_{d}$
\end_inset

, and in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}^{n}M=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{3},x^{2}y,xy^{2},y^{3}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=A/I$
\end_inset

.
 We want to calculate the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremlength}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it suffices to find a composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and calculate its length.
 A composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=M_{6}\subset M_{5}\subset M_{4}\subset M_{3}\subset M_{2}\subset M_{1}\subset M_{0}=M,
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M_{5} & =\langle x^{2},xy^{2},y^{3}\rangle/I\\
M_{4} & =\langle x^{2},y^{2}\rangle/I\\
M_{3} & =\langle x^{2},xy,y^{2}\rangle/I\\
M_{2} & =\langle x,y^{2}\rangle/I\\
M_{1} & =\langle x,y\rangle/I,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}/M_{i+1}\cong A/\langle x,y\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(M)=6$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Injective Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defninjective}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
injective 
\series default
if for every injective homorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 and for every homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

 there exists a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon N\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\circ\varphi=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset N$
\end_inset

, then we will simply say 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 We illustrate this with the following diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} M 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
psi ", swap] & N 
\backslash
arrow[dl, "
\backslash
widetilde{ 
\backslash
psi }", dashed]  
\backslash

\backslash
 E 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An equivalent definition of being injective is given in the following propositio
n:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if the contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{R}(-,E)$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Let 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M' 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi "]  & M 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi "]  & M'' 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
be an exact sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{R}(-,E)$
\end_inset

 is left exact, we only need to check that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
text{Hom}_R (M,E) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi ^{*} "]  & 
\backslash
text{Hom}_R (M',E) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact at 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{R}(M',E)$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\text{Hom}_{R}(M',E)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M'\to M$
\end_inset

 is a monomorphism, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\lambda}\in\text{Hom}_{R}(M',E)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}(\widetilde{\lambda})=\widetilde{\lambda}\circ\varphi=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}(\widetilde{\lambda})=\widetilde{\lambda}\circ\varphi$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 In fact, this map is surjective if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective by definition.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Baer's Criterion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 If we want to determine if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective, then it turns out that we do not necessarily need to check
 that the condition in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defninjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 holds for 
\emph on
every 
\emph default
injective homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

; we only need to check that it holds for every morphism of the type 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 This is called Baer's Criterion.
 Before we show this, let us first show that we need only consider inclusions
 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset N$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if for every inclusion of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset N$
\end_inset

 and for every homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

 there exists a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon N\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{M}=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One direction is obvious.
 To prove the other direction, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an injective homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

 be a homorphism.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective, it induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to\varphi(M)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 be the inverse homomorphism to this isomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(M)\subset N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}\colon\varphi(M)\to E$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism, and so by hypothesis, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon N\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{\varphi(M)}=\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\psi}\circ\varphi & =\widetilde{\psi}|_{\varphi(M)}\circ\varphi\\
 & =\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}\circ\varphi\\
 & =\psi.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will state and prove Baer's Criterion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorembaer}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Baer's Criterion) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if for every ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 and for every homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon I\to E$
\end_inset

 there exists a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon R\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{I}=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One direction is obvious.
 For the other direction, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset N$
\end_inset

 be an inclusion of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism.
 Define the partially ordered set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathscr{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathscr{F}:=\{\psi'\colon M'\to N\mid M\subset M'\subset N\text{ and }\psi'\text{ extends }\psi\}.
\]

\end_inset

and the where partial order 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi'\leq\psi''\text{ if and only if }\psi''\text{ extends }\psi'.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{T}$
\end_inset

 is a totally ordered subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

, then it has an upper bound (namely we take the direct limit of a all 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'\in\mathscr{T}$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore by Zorn's lemma, there is a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'\colon N'\to E$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset N'\subset N$
\end_inset

 which is maximal with respect to the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $N'=N$
\end_inset

.
 We will prove this by contradiciton: assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $N'\neq N$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an element 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in N\backslash N'$
\end_inset

 and consider the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=\{a\in R\mid au\in N'\}.
\]

\end_inset

It is a nonempty proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\notin I$
\end_inset

.
 By hypothesis, the composite 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} I 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
cdot u" ] & N' 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi '"]  & E 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
extends to a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon R\to E$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi''\colon N'+Ru\to E$
\end_inset

 by the formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi''(v+au)=\psi'(v)+\widetilde{\psi}(a)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v+au\in N'+Rn$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this is well-defined, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}+a_{1}u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}+a_{2}u$
\end_inset

 represent the same element in 
\begin_inset Formula $N'+Ru$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}-v_{1}=(a_{1}-a_{2})u$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}-a_{2}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(a_{1}-a_{2})=\psi'((a_{1}-a_{2})u)$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi''(v_{2}+a_{2}u) & =\psi'(v_{2})+\widetilde{\psi}(a_{2})\\
 & =\psi'(v_{2}-(v_{2}-v_{1})))+\widetilde{\psi}(a_{1}+(a_{2}-a_{1}))\\
 & =\psi'(v_{2}+(a_{1}-a_{2})u)+\widetilde{\psi}(a_{1}+(a_{2}-a_{1}))\\
 & =\psi'(v_{1})+\psi'((a_{1}-a_{2})u)+\widetilde{\psi}(a_{1})+\psi'((a_{2}-a_{1})u)\\
 & =\psi'(v_{1})+\widetilde{\psi}(a_{1}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi''$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 We also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi''$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'$
\end_inset

 was maximal, this leads to a contradiction.
 So we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $N'=N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{remext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Saying that every map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon I\to E$
\end_inset

 extends to a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon R\to E$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to saying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ext}_{R}^{1}(R\slash I,E)=0$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, consider the short exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & I 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & R 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & R 
\backslash
slash I 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applying the contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{R}(-,E)$
\end_inset

, we obtain the long exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=30] 
\backslash
text{Hom}_R (I,E) & 
\backslash
text{Hom}_R (R,E) 
\backslash
arrow[l] 
\backslash
arrow[d, phantom, ""{coordinate, name=Z}] & 
\backslash
text{Hom}_R (R 
\backslash
slash I,E) 
\backslash
arrow[l] & 0 
\backslash
arrow[l]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash
  & 0 
\backslash
cong 
\backslash
text{Ext}_R ^1 (R,E) & 
\backslash
mbox{Ext}_R ^1 (R 
\backslash
slash I,E) 
\backslash
arrow[l] 
\backslash
arrow[ull, <-, rounded corners, to path={ -- ([xshift=2ex]
\backslash
tikztostart.east) |- (Z) [near end]
\backslash
tikztonodes -| ([xshift=-2ex]
\backslash
tikztotarget.west) -- (
\backslash
tikztotarget)}]  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's easy to check that this exact sequence implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ext}_{R}^{1}(R\slash I,E)\cong0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{R}(R,E)\to\text{Hom}_{R}(I,E)$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Localization, Direct Sums, and Direct Products of Injective Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmasuminjective}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{\lambda}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 be a colletion of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules indexed by a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a multiplicatively closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if all the 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 are injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if all the 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 are injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an injective, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{S}$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{S}$
\end_inset

-module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if any monomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon E\to M$
\end_inset

 splits, that is, there exists a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\varphi=\mathrm{id}_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}\left(M,\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}\right)\cong\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\text{Hom}_{R}\left(M,E_{\lambda}\right)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{R}\left(-,\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 is exact if and only if the functors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}\left(-,E_{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 are exact for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon I\to E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is injective, the composition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\to E_{\lambda}\hookrightarrow\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

extends to a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon R\to\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\colon\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}\to E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 denote the projection to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

th component, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\circ\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this direction did not depend on the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Converesely, assume each 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theorembaer})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it is enough to show that for an ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, any homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon I\to\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 extends to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated, and so there exists a finite subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\lambda_{1},\dots,\lambda_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{im}\,\varphi & \subseteq\bigoplus_{i=1}^{n}E_{\lambda_{i}}\\
 & \cong\prod_{i=1}^{n}E_{\lambda_{i}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

From (1), we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=1}^{n}E_{\lambda_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is injective, and therefore we may extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon I_{S}\to E_{S}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{S}$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian ring, the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finitely presented, and thus there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon I\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{S}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective, we may choose an extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon R\to E$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}_{S}\colon R_{S}\to E_{S}$
\end_inset

 is an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon I_{S}\to E_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 One direction is obvious, so we only prove the nonobvious direction.
 Assume that any injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map out of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 splits.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

 be any 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 We need to construct a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon N\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\circ\varphi=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, consider the pushout module
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E+_{M}N=(E\times N)\slash\{(\psi(u),-\varphi(u))\mid u\in M\}
\]

\end_inset

together its natural maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{1}\colon E\to E+_{M}N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{2}\colon N\to E+_{M}N$
\end_inset

, given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{1}(v)=[v,0]\qquad\text{and}\qquad\iota_{2}(w)=[0,w]
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in N$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $[v,w]$
\end_inset

 denotes the equivalence class in 
\begin_inset Formula $E+_{M}N$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(v,w)$
\end_inset

 as one of its representatives.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\iota_{1}(\psi(u)) & =[\psi(u),0]\\
 & =[0,\varphi(u)]\\
 & =\iota_{2}(\varphi(u))
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we have a commutative diagram
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  M 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
psi ", swap] & N 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
iota _2 "]  
\backslash

\backslash
 E 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota _1 ", swap] & E + _M N 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\ker\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[v,0]=[0,0]$
\end_inset

 implies if 
\begin_inset Formula $(v,0)=(\psi(u),-\varphi(u))$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u)=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective, and therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v & =\psi(u)\\
 & =\psi(0)\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Therefore by hypothesis the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{1}\colon E\to E+_{M}N$
\end_inset

 splits, say by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\colon E+_{M}N\to E$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\circ\iota_{1}=1_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we obtain a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon N\to E$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}:=\lambda\circ\iota_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\psi}\circ\varphi & =\lambda\circ\iota_{2}\circ\varphi\\
 & =\lambda\circ\iota_{1}\circ\psi\\
 & =\psi,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 has the desired property.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian if and only if every direct sum of injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We proved one direction in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasuminjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For the other direction, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is not Noetherian.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 contains a strictly ascending chain of ideals 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{1}\subsetneq I_{2}\subsetneq I_{3}\subsetneq\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\bigcup_{j}I_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The natural maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\hookrightarrow R\to R\slash I_{j}\hookrightarrow\mathrm{E}_{R}(R\slash I_{j})
\]

\end_inset

give us a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $I\to\prod_{j}\mathrm{E}_{R}(A/I_{j})$
\end_inset

, whose image lies in the submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{j}\mathrm{E}_{R}(R/I_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, note for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I_{k}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 This implies the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 lies in the submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{j=1}^{k-1}\mathrm{E}_{R}(R/I_{j})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Therefore we have a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon I\to\bigoplus_{j}\mathrm{E}_{R}(R/I_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 does not extend to a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $R\to\bigoplus_{j}\mathrm{E}_{R}(R/I_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a flat ring map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an injective as an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is true because
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,E)\cong\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M\otimes_{R}S,E)
\]

\end_inset

and the fact that tensoring with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R\to S$
\end_inset

 be an epimorphism of rings.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an injective as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective as an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is true because
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,E)=\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(N,E)
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Divisible Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
divisible
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $aM=M$
\end_inset

 for every nonzerodivisor 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Image of divisible module is divisible
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\twoheadrightarrow N$
\end_inset

 be a surjective map of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 be a nonzerodivisor and let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N$
\end_inset

.
 We must find a 
\begin_inset Formula $v'\in N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $av'=v$
\end_inset

.
 It will then follow that 
\begin_inset Formula $aN=N$
\end_inset

, which will imply 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective, we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u)=v$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is divisible, we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u'\in M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $au'=u$
\end_inset

.
 Then setting 
\begin_inset Formula $v'=\varphi(u')$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
av' & =a\varphi(u')\\
 & =\varphi(au')\\
 & =\varphi(u)\\
 & =v.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Injectives modules are divisible (with converse being true in a PID)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propinjectiveintegraldomain}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is injective, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
 The converse holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is injective and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 be a nonzerodivisor.
 Then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to aM$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(u)=au
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Thus we obtain a splitting map of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon aM\to M$
\end_inset

.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u & =(\psi\varphi)(u)\\
 & =\psi(\varphi(u))\\
 & =\psi(au)\\
 & =a\psi(u).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $M=aM$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For the converse direction, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID and that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a divisible 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\langle x\rangle\to M$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 be a nonzerodivisor and set 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M=xM$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $u=xv$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon R\to M$
\end_inset

, given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi}(a)=av
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

, extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, it is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\varphi}(bx) & =(bx)v\\
 & =b(xv)\\
 & =bu\\
 & =b\varphi(x)\\
 & =\varphi(bx)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $bx\in\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from Baer's Criterion that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a PID and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is divisible as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-module, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propinjectiveintegraldomain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Decomposition of module over PID
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be any 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 may be decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula $M=D\oplus N$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is divisible and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 has no nontrivial divisible subgroups.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first argue using Zorn's Lemma that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 contains a maximal divisible submdoule.
 Consider the partially ordered set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathscr{F},\subseteq)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 is the family of all divisible submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathscr{F}=\{D\subseteq M\mid D\text{ is divisible submodule of }M\},
\]

\end_inset

and where the partial order 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 is set inclusion.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since the zero module is divisible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{D_{i}\mid i\in I\}$
\end_inset

 be a totally ordered subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}
\]

\end_inset

is a divisible submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and hence an upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{D_{i}\mid i\in I\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To see this, we first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, it is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}$
\end_inset

, then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in D_{i}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\{D_{i}\mid i\in I\}$
\end_inset

 is totally ordered, and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
au+v\in D_{i}\subseteq\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero divisor in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 be an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in D_{i}$
\end_inset

, and as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}$
\end_inset

 is divisible, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\in D_{i}\in\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $av=u$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}D_{i}$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus the conditions for Zorn's Lemma are satisfied and so there exists a
 maximal divisible submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $D\subseteq M$
\end_inset

.
 Since every divisible module over a PID is injective, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is injective, and thus we have a direct sum decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=D\oplus N
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 To finish the proof, assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 has a nontrivial divisible submodule, say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\subseteq N$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $D+L$
\end_inset

 is a divisible submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 which properly contains 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
  Indeed, it is divisible since if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 is a nonzerodivisor and 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in D+L$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in L$
\end_inset

, then we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in L$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $au=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $av=y$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are divisible, and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a(u+v) & =au+av\\
 & =x+y
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $D+L$
\end_inset

 is divisible.
 It also properly contains 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $L\subseteq N$
\end_inset

 is nontrivial.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $D+L$
\end_inset

 is a divisible submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 which properly contains 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction as 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 was chosen to be a maximal divisible submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
label{propquotientfield}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 Then its quotient field 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(A)$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show this using Baer's criterion.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:I\to Q(A)$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-linear map where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=0$
\end_inset

, extend by the zero map.
 Otherwise, let 
\begin_inset Formula $0\neq x\in I$
\end_inset

 and define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:A\to Q(A)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mapsto a\varphi(x)/x$
\end_inset

.
 This map is obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-linear and if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\varphi}(y) & =\frac{y\varphi(x)}{x}\\
 & =\frac{\varphi(yx)}{x}\\
 & =\frac{x\varphi(y)}{x}\\
 & =\varphi(y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaprojectiveinjective}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra, let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 a projective 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{R}(P,E)$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{S}(-,\text{Hom}_{R}(P,E))$
\end_inset

 is exact if and only if the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-\otimes_{S}P,E)$
\end_inset

 is exact, but tensor-hom adjunction.
 Now notice that the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{S}P$
\end_inset

 is exact since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective (and hence flat), and the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-,E)$
\end_inset

 is exact since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(-\otimes_{S}P,E)$
\end_inset

 is a composition of exact functors, and so it must be exact too.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Injective Hulls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now prove that any 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 can be embedded into an injective module.
 We first prove this for 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{injectivezmodule}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then there exists an injective module 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and a monomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 For a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N^{\lor}:=\text{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(N,\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}).
\]

\end_inset

We now have a natural map 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M^{\lor\lor}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $u\mapsto\widehat{u}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{u}(\varphi)=\varphi(u)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\text{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(M,\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M^{\lor\lor}$
\end_inset

 is a monomorphism.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $n:=\mathrm{ord}(u)$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $nu=0$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 being as small as possible) and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\langle u\rangle\to\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 be the unique homomorphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u)=[1/n]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is not the zero map.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is injective, we can extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to a nonzero map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon M\to\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{u}(\widetilde{\varphi}) & =\widetilde{\varphi}(\widehat{u})\\
 & =\varphi(u)\\
 & \neq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{u}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathbb{Z}\to M^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 be a surjection.
 Since the contraviarant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(-,\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

 is left exact, we get an embedding
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M & \to M^{\lor\lor}\\
 & =\text{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\left(M^{\lor},\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}\right)\\
 & \to\text{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\left(\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathbb{Z},\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}\right)\\
 & \cong\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathbb{Q}\slash\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is injective by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasuminjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we prove it for an arbitrary commutative ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then there is an injective module 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and a monomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-injective module 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that we have a monomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\colon M\to E_{1}$
\end_inset

, by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{injectivezmodule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is projective over itself, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,E_{1})$
\end_inset

 is injective as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaprojectiveinjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi\colon M\to\text{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,E_{1})$
\end_inset

 be given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi(u)(a)=\varphi_{1}(au)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear and injective.
 Indeed, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-linear.
 Also, it is injective since if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(u)=0$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\Psi(u)(1)\\
 & =\varphi_{1}(u),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Essential Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset E$
\end_inset

 be an inclusion of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
essential extension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E$
\end_inset

, if every nonzero submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 intersects 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 nontrivially, that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap M\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Such an essential extension is called 
\series bold
maximal
\series default
, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{m}}E$
\end_inset

 if no module properly containing 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, that is, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is maximal if 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subset F$
\end_inset

 where the inlusion is strict, then there exists a submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap M=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if and only if for any nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in E$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u\rangle\cap M\ne0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap M\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset E_{1}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E_{1}\cap N & \supset M\cap N\\
 & \neq0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap E_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cap E_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{1}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M\cap N & =(M\cap E_{1})\cap N\\
 & =M\cap(E_{1}\cap N)\\
 & \neq0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 One direction is obvious, so suppose we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u\rangle\cap M\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in E$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a nonzero element 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
N\cap M & \supset\langle w\rangle\cap M\\
 & \neq0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0:_{M}I\subset_{\mathrm{e}}\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}0:_{M}I^{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}0:_{M}I^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the smallest natural number such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u\mathfrak{m}^{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \neq u\mathfrak{m}^{n-1}\\
 & \subset\langle u\rangle\cap(0:_{M}\mathfrak{m}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the formal power series ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K[[x]]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=R_{x}\slash R$
\end_inset

.
 Every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is killed by a power of the maximal ideal, hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}0:_{M}\mathfrak{m}^{n}.
\]

\end_inset

The 
\series bold
socle 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is defined to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{soc}\,M:=0:_{M}\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by the previous example, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{soc}\,M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}M$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{soc}\,M$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-vector space generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1/x\right]$
\end_inset

, that is, the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{\mathbb{N}}\mathrm{soc}\,M\subset\prod_{\mathbb{N}}M
\]

\end_inset

is not an essential extension since the element
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\left[1/x^{n}\right]\right)\in\prod_{\mathbb{N}}M
\]

\end_inset

does not have a nonzero multiple in 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\mathbb{N}}\mathrm{soc}\,M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Injective Modules are Modules with no Proper Essential Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmainjectiveiffmaximal}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has no proper essential extensions.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is injective and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{\mathrm{e}}E$
\end_inset

 be an essential extension.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is injective, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, that is 
\begin_inset Formula $E=M\oplus N$
\end_inset

 for some submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cap N=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $M=E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has no proper essential extension.
 Embed 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 into an injective module 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a maximal submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cap N=0$
\end_inset

 (Zorn).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E\slash N$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by construction, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $M=E\slash N$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $E=M\oplus N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is injective since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective, by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasuminjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmamaximalessentialextension}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a maximal essential extension.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Embed 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 into an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that there are maximal essential extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 We order the set of essential extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 by inclusion.
 The union of a chain of essential extensions is again essential.
 Therefore, there exists a maximal essential extension by Zorn's lemma.
 We claim that such an extension is a maximal essential extension in general.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be such a maximal essential extension inside 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $N'$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N'$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to N'$
\end_inset

 is an inclusion, and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective, we can extend the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to E$
\end_inset

 to a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:N'\to E$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\varphi)\cap M=0$
\end_inset

 by construction, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective, but this contradicts the maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 inside 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


