\begin_layout Subsection
Injective Resolutions and Injective Dimension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 We say that a complex of injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{E} : E_0  
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _1 "] & E_1  
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
varphi _2 "] & E_2  
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is an 
\series bold
injective resolution 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\psi_{1})=M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 is exact except at 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 is an injective resolution, then we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
minimal injective resolution 
\series default
if and only if each 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the injective hull of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}\left(\psi_{n+1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Every module has a minimal injective resolution, which is unique up to
 isomorphism.
 The 
\series bold
injective dimension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{id}_{A}(M)$
\end_inset

, is the length of this resolution (which may be 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 a multiplicatively closed set.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{id}_{A_{S}}(M_{S})\leq\text{id}_{A}(M).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from exactness of localization and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasuminjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop3.1.10}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 The following conditions are equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{id}(M)\leq n$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n+1}(N,M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n+1}(A/I,M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n+1}(N,M)$
\end_inset

 can be computed from an injective resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3 is trivial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1: Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\to M\to E^{0}\to E^{1}\to E^{2}\to\cdots\to E^{n-1}\to C\to0
\]

\end_inset

be an exact sequence, where the modules 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{j}$
\end_inset

 are injective.
 From the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{i}(A/I,E)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i>0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, the above exact sequence yields the isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ext}_{A}^{1}(A/I,C)\cong\text{Ext}_{A}^{n+1}(A/I,M),
\]

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{1}(A/I,C)=0$
\end_inset

 for all ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is injective from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Remark~(
\backslash
ref{remext})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can sharpen 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.1.10})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian ring.
 We first observe:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmanoetherianext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

 an integer.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Supp}(N)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n}(N,M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 has a finite filtration whose factors are isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Supp}(N)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the lemma follows from the additivity of the vanish of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n}(-,M)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{id}_{A}(M)\leq n;$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n+1}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop3.1.13}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},k)$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian local ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 a prime ideal different from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n+1}(A/\mathfrak{q},M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\in\mathbf{V}(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\neq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We choose an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{m}\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The element is 
\begin_inset Formula $(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

-regular, and therefore we get the exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A/ 
\backslash
mathfrak{p} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
cdot x" ]  & A/
\backslash
mathfrak{p} 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & A/ 
\backslash
langle x,
\backslash
mathfrak{p} 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which induces the exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
text{Ext}_A ^n (A/
\backslash
mathfrak{p} , M) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
cdot x" ] & 
\backslash
text{Ext}_A ^n (A/
\backslash
mathfrak{p} , M) 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 
\backslash
text{Ext}_A ^{n+1} (A/ 
\backslash
langle x, 
\backslash
mathfrak{p} 
\backslash
rangle , M).
 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(x,\mathfrak{p})\subset\{\mathfrak{q}\in\mathbf{V}(\mathfrak{p})\mid\mathfrak{q}\neq\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmanoetherianext})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and our assumption imply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ext}_{A}^{n+1}(A/\langle x,\mathfrak{p}\rangle,M)=0,
\]

\end_inset

so that multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on the finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{n}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)$
\end_inset

 is a surjective homomorphism.
 The desired result follows from Nakayama's lemma.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It is now easy to derive the following useful formula for the injective
 dimension of a finitely generated module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop3.1.14}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m},k)$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian local ring, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{id}_{A}(M)=\text{sup}\{i\mid\text{Ext}_{A}^{i}(k,M)\neq0\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\text{sup}\{i\mid\text{Ext}_{A}^{i}(k,M)\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{id}_{A}(M)\geq t$
\end_inset

.
 To prove the converse inequality, note that the repeated application of
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.1.13})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{i}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $i>t$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{id}_{A}(M)\leq t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To see how the repeated application of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.1.13})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{i}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $i>t$
\end_inset

, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(\mathfrak{p})=\{\mathfrak{m}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}^{t+1}(A/\mathfrak{m},M)=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{t}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}^{t+2}(A/\mathfrak{m},M)=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{t+1}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Next, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathbf{V}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\neq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we've just shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{t+1}(A/\mathfrak{p},M)=0$
\end_inset

, and this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{t}(A/\mathfrak{q},M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop21.10}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-regular and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-regular element, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{E} : E_0  
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _1 "] & E_1  
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
varphi _2 "] & E_2  
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots  
\backslash
