\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a minimal injective resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M/xM$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $A/x$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{id}_{A/x}(M/xM)=\text{id}_{A}(M)-1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and if 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module annihilated by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ext}_{A}^{i+1}(N,M)\cong\text{Ext}_{A/x}^{i}(N,M/xM)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaprojectiveinjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}'$
\end_inset

 are injective 
\begin_inset Formula $(A/x)$
\end_inset

-modules.
 The homology of the complex 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  
\backslash
text{Hom}_A (A/x , 
\backslash
mathcal{E} ) : E_0 ' 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _1 "] & E_1 '  
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _2 "] & E_2 '  
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
varphi _3 "] & E_3 '  
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is by definintion 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{*}(A/x,M)$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an essential submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 contains no submodule annihilated by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

 contains no submodule annihilated by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}'=0$
\end_inset

, and we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{A}(A/x,\mathcal{E})=\mathcal{E}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{*}(A/x,M)$
\end_inset

 instead from the free resolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
cdot x "] & A 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A/x 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0, 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{1}(A/x,M)=M/xM$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A}^{i}(A/x,M)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}'$
\end_inset

 is an injective resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M/xM$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the numbering of the terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}'$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ext}_{A/x}^{i}(N,M/xM)$
\end_inset

 is the homology of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{A/x}(N,\mathcal{E}')$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{A/x}(N,E_{j+1}');$
\end_inset

 strictly speaking, we should say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}'[1]$
\end_inset

 is an injective resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M/xM$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}'$
\end_inset

 is minimal, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}\left(\varphi_{n+1}:E_{n}'\to E_{n+1}'\right)$
\end_inset

 is the intersection of the essential submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}\left(\varphi_{n+1}:E_{n}\to E_{n+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}'$
\end_inset

, and is thus essential in 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}'$
\end_inset

.
 It follows at once that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{id}_{A/x}(M/xM)=\text{id}_{A}(M)-1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 annihilates the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, then every map from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 to an 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 has image killed by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Hom}_{A}(N,\mathcal{E})=\text{Hom}_{A}(N,\mathcal{E}')=\text{Hom}_{A/x}(N,\mathcal{E}').
\]

\end_inset

Taking homology, and taking into account the shift in numbering, we get
 the last statement of the proposition.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 is a local ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-regular and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-regular, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{pd}_{A/x}(M/xM)=\text{pd}_{A}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 The idea behind that proof was to start with a minimal projective resolution
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  
\backslash
mathcal{P} : 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] & P_2  
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _2 "] & P_1  
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
varphi _1 "] & P_0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and show that the sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  
\backslash
mathcal{P} 
\backslash
otimes ( A/x ): 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] & P_2 / xP_2  
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
overline{ 
\backslash
varphi  }_2 "] & P_1 / xP_1  
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
overline{ 
\backslash
varphi } _1 "] & P_0 /xP_0  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
was a minimal projective resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M/xM$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To exploit this result, we need to know the modules of finite injective
 dimension over a zero-dimensional ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a local Cohen-Macaulay ring.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a maximal Cohen-Macaulay module of finite injective dimension, then
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{id}_{A}(M)=\text{dim}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(A)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a direct sum of copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{A}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cong\omega_{A}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{End}_{A}(M)=A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose first that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(A)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D=\text{Hom}_{A}(-,\omega_{A})$
\end_inset

 be the dualizing functor.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has finite injective dimension, then applying 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 to an injective resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(M)$
\end_inset

 is a module of finite projective dimension, and is thus free by the Auslander-B
uchsbaum formula.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 again we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $M=D^{2}M$
\end_inset

 is a direct sum of copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(A)=\omega_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, we see that the endomorphism ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the same as the endomorphism ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(A)=d$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, then we may choose a regular sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{d}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that is a regular sequence on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and use 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop21.10})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to conclude that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{id}_{A}(M) & =d+\text{id}_{A/\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{d}\rangle}\left(M/\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{d}\rangle M\right)\\
 & =d+0\\
 & =d.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Injective Modules over Noetherian Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subset A$
\end_inset

 a multiplicatively closed set and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(M)_{S}\cong E_{A_{S}}(M_{S})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(M)_{S}$
\end_inset

 is an injective hull of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 We know from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasuminjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(M)_{S}$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}$
\end_inset

-module.
 It remains to be show that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(M)_{S}$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $e/s\in E_{A}(M)_{S}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in E_{A}(M)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}(e/s)\cap M_{S}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $e/s$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $e/1$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}(e/s)=A_{S}(e/1)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{1}:=M:_{A}e=\left\{ a\in A\mid ae\in M\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(M)$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $ae\neq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in I_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated, say 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}=\langle a_{1},\dots,a_{k}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}e/1\in M_{S}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 If, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}e/1\neq0$
\end_inset

, we are done.
 So assume 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}e/1=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}\in S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}(a_{i}e)=a_{i}(s_{1}e)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}(e/1)=A_{S}(s_{1}e/1)$
\end_inset

, we may replace 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}e$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{2}:=M:_{A}s_{1}e=I_{1}:s_{1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(M)$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a(s_{1}e)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in I_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}\supsetneq I_{1}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 annihilates 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}e$
\end_inset

.
 Proceeding inductively, we obtain a sequence of ideals 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{1}\subset I_{2}\subset\cdots,
\]

\end_inset

which must terminate since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, say 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}=I_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then it easily follows that there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in I_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a(s_{n}\cdots s_{1}e)/1\neq0$
\end_inset

, for if this was not the case, then we could construct an 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 as above, and deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n+1}\supsetneq I_{n}$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{i=1}^{n}E\left(M_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is injective, and by the previous lemma it is essential over 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{i=1}^{n}M_{i}$
\end_inset

, hence we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the next theorem, we determine the indecomposable injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules of a Noetherian ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
decomposable 
\series default
if there exist nonzero submodules 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1},M_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M=M_{1}\oplus M_{2}$
\end_inset

; otherwise it is 
\series bold
indecomposable
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

, the module 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is indecomposable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\neq0$
\end_inset

 be an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Ass}(E)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is indecomposable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E\cong E(A/\mathfrak{p}).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p},\mathfrak{q}\in\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})\cong E(A/\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is decomposable.
 Then there exist nonzero submodules 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1},N_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}\cap N_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(N_{1}\cap(A/\mathfrak{p})\right)\cap\left(N_{2}\cap(A/\mathfrak{p})\right)=(N_{1}\cap N_{2})\cap(A/\mathfrak{p})=0.
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}\subset_{e}E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{1}\cap(A/\mathfrak{p})\neq0\neq N_{2}\cap(A/\mathfrak{p}).
\]

\end_inset

This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a domain: 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}\cap(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}\cap(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 are ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Denoting these ideals as 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively, in a domain we have 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cap I_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 may be considered as a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Ass}(E)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that there exists an injective hull 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})\subset E$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is injective, it is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Statement 3 follows from the next lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma3.2.7}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(M)=\text{Ass}(E(M))$
\end_inset

; in particular, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{p}\}=\text{Ass}(E(A/\mathfrak{p}))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $k(\mathfrak{p})\cong\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}),E(A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{p}})\cong\text{Hom}_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p},E(A/\mathfrak{p}))_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(M)\subset\text{Ass}(E(M))$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Ass}(E(M))$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in E(M)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=0:e$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset_{e}E(M)$
\end_inset

 is essential, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Ae\cap M\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ae\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0:ae & =(0:e):a\\
 & =\mathfrak{p}:a\\
 & =\mathfrak{p},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{p}}\cong E_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}))$
\end_inset

, we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m,}k)$
\end_inset

 is local and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is the maximal ideal.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{A}(k,E(k))$
\end_inset

 may be identified with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\{e\in E(k)\mid\mathfrak{m}e=0\}=\text{Soc}(E(k)),
\]

\end_inset

which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V\neq k$
\end_inset

, then there exists a nonzero vector subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\cap W=0$
\end_inset

.
 This, however, contradicts the essentiality of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $k\subset E(k)$
\end_inset

.
 The second isomorphism follows from
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}),E(A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{p}})=\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(A_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}},E(A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{p}})\cong\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}((A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{p}},E(A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{p}})\cong\text{Hom}_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p},E(A/\mathfrak{p}))_{\mathfrak{p}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The importance of the indecomposable injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules results from the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring.
 Every injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a direct sum of indecomposable injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules, and this decomposition is unique in the following sense: for any
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

, the number of indecomposable summands in the decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 which are isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 (and not on the particular decomposition).
 In fact, this number equals 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{dim}_{k(\mathfrak{p})}\left(\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}),E_{\mathfrak{p}})\right).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 of all subsets of the set of indecomposable injective submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 with the property: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

, then the sum of all modules belonging to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is direct.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 is partially ordered by inclusion.
 By Zorn's lemma it has a maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}'$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be the sum of all the modules in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}'$
\end_inset

.
 The module 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a direct sum of injective modules, and hence is itself injective.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $E=F\oplus H$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is injective since it is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $H\neq0$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Ass}(H)$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may enlarge 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}'$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

, contradicting the maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}'$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $H=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E=F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the given decomposition.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}),E_{\mathfrak{p}})\cong\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}\left(k(\mathfrak{p}),\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}(E_{\lambda})_{\mathfrak{p}}\right)\cong\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}\left(k(\mathfrak{p}),(E_{\lambda})_{\mathfrak{p}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $k(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated in the second isomorphism.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma3.2.7})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}\left(k(\mathfrak{p}),(E_{\lambda})_{\mathfrak{p}}\right)\cong\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda_{0}}\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}\left(k(\mathfrak{p}),(E_{\lambda})_{\mathfrak{p}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{0}=\{\lambda\in\Lambda\mid E_{\lambda}\cong E(A/\mathfrak{p})\}$
\end_inset

.
 If we again use 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma3.2.7})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we finally get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}),E_{\mathfrak{p}})\cong\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda_{0}}\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}\left(k(\mathfrak{p}),(E_{\lambda})_{\mathfrak{p}}\right)\cong k(\mathfrak{p})^{\Lambda_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremdirectsum}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\cong\bigoplus_{i}E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p}_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, any such direct sum is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 By Zorn's Lemma, there exists a maximal family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 of injective submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}\cong E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p}_{i})$
\end_inset

, and their sum in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a direct sum.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E'=\bigoplus_{i}E_{i}$
\end_inset

, which is an injective module, and hence is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 There exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $E''$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E'\bigoplus E''$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E''\neq0$
\end_inset

, pick a nonzero element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E''$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be an associated prime of 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}\hookrightarrow Ax\subseteq E''$
\end_inset

, so there is a copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $E''$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E''=E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})\bigoplus E'''$
\end_inset

, contradicting the maximality of the family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem2.5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $k=A_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzcd} E 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
cdot x "]  & E  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{E}\mathfrak{p}=k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $k\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-torsion and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(E)=\{\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k,E)=k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k,E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q})_{\mathfrak{p}})=0$
\end_inset

 for primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\neq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(A/\mathfrak{p})=k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propquotientfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 contains a copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}\subseteq k\subseteq E$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is injective on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and hence also on its essential extension 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 The submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $xE$
\end_inset

 is injective, so it is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $k\subseteq xE\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 are essential extensions, so 
\begin_inset Formula $xE=E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{E}\mathfrak{p}=0:_{E}\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a vector space over the field 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and hence the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $k\subseteq0:_{E}\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 splits.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $k\subseteq0:_{E}\mathfrak{p}\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension, so 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{E}\mathfrak{p}=k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The containment 
\begin_inset Formula $k\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules, hence also of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq M$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-modules, pick 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 has a nonzero multiple 
\begin_inset Formula $(a/s)m\in E$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in A\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $am$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq M$
\end_inset

 is an essential extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $M=E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\in\text{Ass}(E)$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{A}x=\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 is essential, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 has a nonzero multiple 
\begin_inset Formula $y=ax$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 But then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=0:_{A}y=0:_{E}ax=(0:_{E}x):_{A}a$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(E)=\{\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{E}x$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is the only associated prime of 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{E}x\hookrightarrow E$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{E}x\supset\mathfrak{p}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and this proves our claim.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the first assertion, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k,E)=\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(A_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}},E)\cong0:_{E}\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}=k.
\]

\end_inset

For the first assertion, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subsetneq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{n}\subsetneq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore since 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

-torsion, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q})_{\mathfrak{p}}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subsetneq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k,E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q})_{\mathfrak{p}})\cong0:_{E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q})_{\mathfrak{p}}}\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}=0:_{E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q})}\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}.
\]

\end_inset

If this is nonzero, then there is a nonzero element of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 killed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, which forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q}))=\{\mathfrak{q}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem2.5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzcd} E_A (A/ 
\backslash
mathfrak{p} ) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
cdot x "]  & (A/ 
\backslash
mathfrak{p} )  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})=E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p},E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p}))=0:_{E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})}\mathfrak{p}=0:_{E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})_{\mathfrak{p}}}k(\mathfrak{p})=0:_{E_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}))}k(\mathfrak{p})=\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}),E_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}))=k(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p}))=\{\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-torsion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}),E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{q})_{\mathfrak{p}})=0$
\end_inset

 for primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\neq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(A/\mathfrak{p})=k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
