end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=\bigoplus_{\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec}(A)}E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p})^{\alpha_{\mathfrak{p}}}
\]

\end_inset

and the numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 are independent of the direct sum decomposition.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremdirectsum})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, there is a direct sum
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\cong\bigoplus_{i}E_{A}(A/\mathfrak{p}_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theorem2.5})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

-vector space 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Hom}_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}(k(\mathfrak{p}),E_{\mathfrak{p}}),
\]

\end_inset

which does not depend on the decomposition.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Flatness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
flat 
\series default
if for every injective homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon L\to N$
\end_inset

, the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $L\otimes_{R}M\to N\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 is again injective.
 An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is called flat if it is flat as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat if and only if the covariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 Indeed, the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 is already right-exact, and being left-exact is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 being flat.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Free modules are flat.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash x$
\end_inset

 not a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be any finitely generated ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\slash Ix\cong I\otimes_{R}R\slash x\to I\left(R\slash x\right)\cong I\slash(I\cap x)
\]

\end_inset

is injective if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $Ix=I\cap x$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then this map is not injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]/\langle xy,y^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra via the unique map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=\overline{x}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is not flat as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle\otimes_{R}A\to\overline{x}A$
\end_inset

 is not injective.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\otimes\overline{y}\mapsto\overline{xy}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $xA$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $x\otimes\overline{y}\neq0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle\otimes_{A}B$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Criterion for Flatness Using Tor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremtorflat}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat if and only if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)\cong0
\]

\end_inset

for all finitely generated ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{remflatrmodiexact}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Before we give a proof, we first make the following observation; namely
 that if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)\cong0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Indeed, applying 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 to the short exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & I 
\backslash
arrow[r] & R 
\backslash
arrow[r] & R 
\backslash
slash I 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
gives us the exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{longexfromtor}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
cong 
\backslash
text{Tor}_1 ^R (R,M) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
text{Tor}_1 ^R (R 
\backslash
slash I,M) 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & I 
\backslash
otimes _R M 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & R 
\backslash
otimes _R M 
\backslash
cong M.
  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the exact sequence 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{longexfromtor})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)\cong0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Remark~(
\backslash
ref{remflatrmodiexact})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)\cong0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)\cong0$
\end_inset

 for all finitely generated ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)\cong0$
\end_inset

 for all finitely generated ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective for all finitely generated ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Remark~(
\backslash
ref{remflatrmodiexact})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 What we need to show is that, for any injective map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon L\to N$
\end_inset

, the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $L\otimes_{R}M\to N\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 First consider the case of the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal (not necessarily finitely generated).
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is not injective.
 Choose
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}\otimes u_{i}\in I\otimes_{R}M
\]

\end_inset

different from zero with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}u_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}:=\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}\otimes u_{i}\in I_{0}\otimes_{R}M
\]

\end_inset

and, therefore, by assumption, it has to be zero.
 In particular, its image in 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 has to be zero too, which is a contradiction.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective for all ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we consider the more general case.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon L\to N$
\end_inset

 be an injective map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L\otimes_{R}M\to N\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 is not injective, then there exists
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}u_{i}\otimes v_{i}\in L\otimes_{A}M
\]

\end_inset

different from zero with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\iota(u_{i})\otimes v_{i}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{0}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\iota(u_{i})R$
\end_inset

, this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $L\otimes_{A}M\to N_{0}\otimes_{A}M$
\end_inset

 is not injective.
 So by passing to 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{0}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated, we can find an increasing chain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=L_{0}\subset L_{1}\subset\cdots\subset L_{r}=N
\]

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules such that each quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i+1}\slash L_{i}$
\end_inset

 is generated by one element, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i+1}\slash L_{i}\cong R\slash I_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the map 
\begin_inset Formula $L\otimes_{R}M\to N\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 is equal to the composition of the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}\otimes_{A}M\to L_{i+1}\otimes_{A}M$
\end_inset

, it is enough to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}\otimes_{A}M\to L_{i+1}\otimes_{A}M$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We have therefore reduced the statement to the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash N\cong R\slash I$
\end_inset

.
 Now, consider the exact sequence
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
text{Tor}_1 ^R (R 
\backslash
slash I ,M) = 
\backslash
text{Tor}_1 ^R (L 
\backslash
slash N ,M) 
\backslash
arrow[r] &  N 
\backslash
otimes _R M 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & L 
\backslash
otimes _R M.
 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)=0$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $L\otimes_{A}M\to N\otimes_{A}M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Criterion for Flatness Using Equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to give another criterion for flatness, in terms of equations in
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, but first we need a lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{tensorzero}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an indexing set, let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\in M$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\langle v_{i}\mid i\in I\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}u_{i}\otimes v_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Of course, there are only finitely many indices 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

 in such a sum.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 if and only if there exists an indexing set 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 and there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{u}_{j}\in M$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in J$
\end_inset

, such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j\in J}a_{ij}\widetilde{u}_{j}=u_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, and;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}a_{ij}v_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in J$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j\in J}a_{ij}\widetilde{u}_{j}=u_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}a_{ij}v_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{i\in I}u_{i}\otimes v_{i} & =\sum_{i\in I}\left(\sum_{j\in J}a_{ij}\widetilde{u}_{j}\right)\otimes v_{i}\\
 & =\sum_{j\in J}\widetilde{u}_{j}\otimes\left(\sum_{i\in I}a_{ij}v_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j\in J}\widetilde{u}_{j}\otimes0\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}u_{i}\otimes v_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} F_1 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
lambda "] & F_0 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
pi "] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
be a presentation of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that there is a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{j}\}_{j\in J}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(f_{j})=\sum_{i\in I}a_{ij}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(e_{i})=v_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in J$
\end_inset

.
 Now apply 
\begin_inset Formula $M\otimes_{R}-$
\end_inset

 to the presentation to get an exact sequence:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} M 
\backslash
otimes _R F_1 
\backslash
arrow[r," 1 
\backslash
otimes 
\backslash
lambda "] & M 
\backslash
otimes _R F_0 
\backslash
arrow[r," 1 
\backslash
otimes 
\backslash
pi "] & M 
\backslash
otimes N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In these terms our assumption reads, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1\otimes\pi)(\sum_{i\in I}u_{i}\otimes e_{i})=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}u_{i}\otimes e_{i}\in\ker(1\otimes\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 By the exactness of the diagram above, there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j\in J}\widetilde{u}_{j}\otimes f_{j}\in M\otimes_{A}F_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1\otimes\lambda)(\sum_{j\in J}\widetilde{u}_{j}\otimes f_{j})=\sum_{i\in I}u_{i}\otimes e_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{i\in I}u_{i}\otimes e_{i} & =(1\otimes\lambda)(\sum_{j\in J}\widetilde{u}_{j}\otimes f_{j})\\
 & =\sum_{j\in J}1(\widetilde{u}_{j})\otimes\lambda(f_{j})\\
 & =\sum_{j\in J}\widetilde{u}_{j}\otimes\left(\sum_{i\in I}a_{ij}e_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i\in I}\left(\sum_{j\in J}a_{ij}\widetilde{u}_{j}\right)\otimes e_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}=\sum_{j\in J}a_{ij}\widetilde{u}_{j}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $M\otimes_{R}F_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 To show 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}a_{ij}v_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}a_{ij}v_{i}=\pi(\lambda(f_{j}))=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{flatequation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat if and only if the following condition is satisfied: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{r}a_{i}u_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{u}_{j}\in M$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{s}a_{ij}\widetilde{u}_{j}=u_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,r$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{r}a_{ij}a_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat.
 Suppose
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{r}a_{i}u_{i}=0,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $I:=\langle a_{1},\dots,a_{r}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

, induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

, is injective.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{r}a_{i}\otimes u_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, and the result follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{tensorzero})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, assume that the condition above is satisfied, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated ideal.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremtorflat})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it suffices to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)=0$
\end_inset

, or equivalently, that the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{r}a_{i}\otimes u_{i}\in I\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}a_{i}u_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then again by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{tensorzero})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{r}a_{i}\otimes u_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle a\rangle\subset R$
\end_inset

 be a principal ideal.
 Then the preceding proof shows that the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if the following condition holds: 
\begin_inset Formula $au=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 implies that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{s}\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{u}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{u}_{s}\in M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sum_{i=1}^{s}a_{i}\widetilde{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $aa_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ann}_{M}(a)\subset\text{Ann}_{R}(a)\cdot M.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the other inclusion is obvious, we have shown
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a principal ideal ring.
 Then an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat if and only if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ann}_{M}(a)=\text{Ann}_{A}(a)\cdot M
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for every 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integral, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat if and only if it is torsion free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\varepsilon]$
\end_inset

-module is flat if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ann}_{M}(\varepsilon)=\varepsilon M$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash\varepsilon M\cong\varepsilon M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finitely Generated Flat Modules over Local Ring are Free
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 be a local ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Moreover, let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{k}\in M$
\end_inset

 such that their classes 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}_{1},\dots,\overline{u}_{k}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{k}$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent.
 In particular, a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module is flat if and only if it is free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We use induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 and assume 
\begin_inset Formula $au_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{flatequation})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{u}_{j}\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}a_{j}\widetilde{u}_{j}=u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $aa_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\notin\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Assume the corollary is proved for 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}u_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{flatequation})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 again and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{u}_{j}\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}a_{ij}\widetilde{u}_{j}=u_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}a_{ij}a_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}\notin\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{kj}\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{k-1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=\sum_{i=1}^{k-1}h_{i}a_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}=-a_{ij}/a_{kj}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}u_{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k-1}a_{i}u_{i}+a_{k}u_{k}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k-1}a_{i}u_{i}+\sum_{i=1}^{k-1}h_{i}a_{i}u_{k}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k-1}a_{i}(u_{i}+h_{i}u_{k}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The induction hypothesis implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\cdots=a_{k-1}=0$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 by the base case.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
More Properties of Flat Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmasuminjective}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{M_{\lambda}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 be a colletion of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules indexed by a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a multiplicatively closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}M_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is flat if and only if all the 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 are flat.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M_{S}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{S}$
\end_inset

-module, and hence a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Since we have isomorophisms
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N\otimes_{R}\left(\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}M_{\lambda}\right)\cong\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\left(N\otimes_{R}M_{\lambda}\right)
\]

\end_inset

natural in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{R}\left(\bigoplus_{\lambda\in\Lambda}M_{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 is exact if and only if the functors 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{R}M_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 are exact for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{S}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Since localization is exact and commutes with tensors products, we see
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective implies 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{S}\otimes_{R_{S}}M_{S}\to M_{S}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{S}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{S}$
\end_inset

-module.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{S}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I\otimes_{R}M_{S} & \cong I\otimes_{R}(R_{S}\otimes_{R_{S}}M_{S})\\
 & \cong(I\otimes_{R}R_{S})\otimes_{R_{S}}M_{S}\\
 & \cong I_{S}\otimes_{R_{S}}M_{S}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus injectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{R}M_{S}\to M_{S}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to injectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{S}\otimes_{R}M_{S}\to M_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be a projective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is flat.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that every free module is flat.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is flat as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and every free module is a direct sum copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasuminjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies every free module is flat.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\oplus K\cong F$
\end_inset

.
 Then it follows 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasuminjective})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is flat since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is flat.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Flat Modules are not necessarily Projective
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-module that is not projective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{proplocalizationisflat})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-module, so we just need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is not projective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\bigoplus_{i\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 be the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-linear map defined on the standard basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{i\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(e_{n})=\frac{1}{n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon\mathbb{Q}\to\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 be the identity map.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective since if 
\begin_inset Formula $m/n\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(me_{n})=m/n$
\end_inset

.
 However there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon\mathbb{Q}\to\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=\varphi\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, observe that the injective map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}\to\prod_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}
\]

\end_inset

induces the injective map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\left(\mathbb{Q},\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}\right)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\left(\mathbb{Q},\prod_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}\right)
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(\mathbb{Q},-)$
\end_inset

 is a left-exact covariant functor.
 Therefore the injection
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\left(\mathbb{Q},\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}\right) & \to\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\left(\mathbb{Q},\prod_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}\right)\\
 & \cong\prod_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\left(\mathbb{Q},\mathbb{Z}\right)\\
 & \cong0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\left(\mathbb{Q},\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}\right)\cong0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus the only 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is the zero map.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Base Change
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a flat ring map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is injective as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is true because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,E)=\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(M\otimes_{R}S,E)$
\end_inset

 and the fact that tensoring with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Local Criteria for Flatness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we give criteria for flatness over local rings.
 We shall weaken the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R\slash I,M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 to just 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{R}(R/\mathfrak{m},M)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 the maximal ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 The following conditions are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-module for all prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

-module for all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset


\series bold
-Mod 
\series default
denote the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
Mod 
\series default
denote the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Then localization is full as a functor.
 In particular, every injective map of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-modules has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\mathfrak{p}}:N_{\mathfrak{p}}\to L_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an injective map 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $i\otimes1:N\otimes_{A}M\to L\otimes_{A}M$
\end_inset

 is also injective since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Since localization is exact as a functor and commutes with tensor products,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{\mathfrak{p}}\otimes1:N_{\mathfrak{p}}\otimes_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}M_{\mathfrak{p}}\to L_{\mathfrak{p}}\otimes_{A_{\mathfrak{p}}}M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is an injective map of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is flat as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Trivial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 denote the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset A$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(1\otimes\varphi)=0$
\end_inset

 by showing 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(1\otimes\varphi)_{\mathfrak{m}}=0$
\end_inset

 for all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subset A$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subset A$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary maximal ideal.
 By hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

-module.
 Since localization is exact as functor, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\mathfrak{m}}:I_{\mathfrak{m}}\subset A_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is injective, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is flat as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

-module, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $1\otimes\varphi_{\mathfrak{m}}:I_{\mathfrak{m}}\otimes_{A_{\mathfrak{m}}}M_{\mathfrak{m}}\to I_{\mathfrak{m}}\otimes_{A_{\mathfrak{m}}}M_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is injective as well.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \cong\text{Ker}(1\otimes\varphi_{\mathfrak{m}})\\
 & =\text{Ker}((1\otimes\varphi)_{\mathfrak{m}})\\
 & =\text{Ker}(1\otimes\varphi)_{\mathfrak{m}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which proves the claim.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem7.4.2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(B,\mathfrak{n})$
\end_inset

 be Noetherian local rings, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}B\subset\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(A/\mathfrak{m},M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(A/\mathfrak{m},M)=0$
\end_inset

, by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremtorflat})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(A/\mathfrak{m},M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset A$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 We have to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{A}M\to M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 We first claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{n=0}^{\infty}\mathfrak{m}^{n}\cdot(I\otimes_{A}M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes_{A}M$
\end_inset

 as a 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-module via the 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-module structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 It is finitely generated as a 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-module, and therefore by Krull's Intersection Theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{n=0}^{\infty}\mathfrak{n}^{n}\cdot(I\otimes_{A}M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}B\subset\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 implies the claim.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\text{Ker}(I\otimes_{A}M\to M)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap_{n=0}^{\infty}\mathfrak{m}^{n}\cdot(I\otimes_{A}M)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 To prove this, we consider the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\mathfrak{m}^{n}I)\otimes_{A}M\to I\otimes_{A}M.
\]

\end_inset

The image of this map is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n}\cdot(I\otimes_{A}M)$
\end_inset

.
 Using the lemma of Artin-Rees, we obtain an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{s}\cap I\subset\mathfrak{m}^{n}I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, it is enough to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in the image of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\mathfrak{m}^{n}\cap I)\otimes_{A}M\to I\otimes_{A}M
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 From the exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} ( 
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n 
\backslash
cap I ) 
\backslash
otimes _A M  
\backslash
arrow[r] & I 
\backslash
otimes _A M  
\backslash
arrow[r]  & (  I / 
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n 
\backslash
cap I ) 
\backslash
otimes _A M  
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we deduce that it is sufficient to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(I/\mathfrak{m}^{n}\cap I)\otimes_{A}M$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the following commutative diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} I 
\backslash
otimes _A M  
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
gamma "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
alpha ", swap] & (  I / 
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n 
\backslash
cap I ) 
\backslash
otimes _A M  
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
pi "]  
\backslash

\backslash
 M 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
beta ", swap]  & (  A / 
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n ) 
\backslash
otimes _A M  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\circ\gamma(x)=0$
\end_inset

, and it is sufficient to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 To prove this, consider the following exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & I / ( 
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n 
\backslash
cap I )   
\backslash
arrow[r] & A /  
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n   
\backslash
arrow[r] & A / (I + 
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n  )  
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which induces an exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
text{Tor} _1 ^A (A / (I + 
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n  ), M) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & (I / ( 
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n 
\backslash
cap I )) 
\backslash
otimes _A M   
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
pi "] & ( A /  
\backslash
mathfrak {m}^n ) 
\backslash
otimes _A M.
    
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see that, finally, it suffices to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(A/(I+\mathfrak{m}^{n}),M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $A/(I+\mathfrak{m}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module of finite length.
 Therefore, the following lemma proves the theorem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 be a local ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(A/\mathfrak{m},M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(P,M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of finite length.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We use induction on the length.
 The case 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{length}(P)=1$
\end_inset

 is clear because it implies 
\begin_inset Formula $P=A/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset P$
\end_inset

 be a proper submodule, then we obtain the exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
text{Tor} _1 ^A (N,M) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
text{Tor} _1 ^A (P,M)   
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
text{Tor} _1 ^A (P/N,M)    
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By the induction hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(N,M)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(P/N,M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tor}_{1}^{A}(P,M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=K[x,y,z]/\langle x-zy\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 be the map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y)=y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

 corresponds tof the 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

-plane, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec}(B)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blown up
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

-plane.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

, induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\#}:\text{Spec}(B)\to\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 We calculate the inverse images of some points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{i,j}=\langle x-i,x-j\rangle$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Max}(A)\subset\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{0,0}) & =\langle x-zy,x,y\rangle=\langle x,y\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{1,0}) & =\langle x-zy,x-1,y\rangle=\langle1\rangle=B\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{1,1}) & =\langle x-zy,x-1,y-1\rangle=\langle x-1,y-1,z-1\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So there is one point which maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{1,1}$
\end_inset

, no points which maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{1,0}$
\end_inset

, and a whole line of points which maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{0,0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename 20180210_132406.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[y,z]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 be the map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y)=y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(z)=z$
\end_inset

, then it's easy to see 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=K[x,y]/\langle xy\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 be the map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y)=y$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{0}) & =\langle xy,y\rangle=\langle y\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{1}) & =\langle xy,y-1\rangle=\langle x,y-1\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Projective Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
projective 
\series default
if for every surjective homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 and for every homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon P\to N$
\end_inset

 there exists a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon P\to M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\widetilde{\psi}=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 We illustrate this with the following diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} & P 
\backslash
arrow[dl, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
psi }
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, dashed,swap] 
\backslash
arrow[d, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
psi 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

M 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi ", swap,twoheadrightarrow]   & N    
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An equivalent definition of being injective is given in the following propositio
n:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is projective if and only if the covariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}_{R}(P,-)$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of Projective Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Free Modules are Projective
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module is projective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be a surjective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon F\to N$
\end_inset

 be any 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, we choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\in M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u_{i})=\psi(e_{i})$
\end_inset

 (such a choice is possible as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective).
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon F\to M$
\end_inset

 to be the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\psi}(e_{i})=u_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi\circ\widetilde{\psi})(e_{i}) & =\varphi(\widetilde{\psi}(e_{i}))\\
 & =\varphi(u_{i})\\
 & =\psi(e_{i}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\widetilde{\psi}=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Equivalent Conditions for being Projective
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 The following statements are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every short exact sequence of the form 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{projectivesplit}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 
\backslash
psi 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

]   & P   
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

is split exact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show 1 implies 2.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective.
 Then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon P\to M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\widetilde{\psi}=1_{P}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 splits 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{projectivesplit})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show 2 implies 3.
 Suppose every short exact sequence of the form 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{projectivesplit})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is split exact.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon F\to P$
\end_inset

 be a surjective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map from a free module 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 denote the kernel of this map.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 could be the free module with generators 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{u}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in P$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon F\to P$
\end_inset

 could be the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\delta_{u})=u$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in P$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have a short exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K 
\backslash
arrow[r] & F 
\backslash
arrow[r]   & P   
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}.
\end_layout

\end_inset

This short exact sequence splits by assumption, and thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $F\cong K\oplus P$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally we show 3 implies 1.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a direct summan of a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, say 
\begin_inset Formula $P\oplus K\cong F$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is free and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is some other 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}\colon F\to P$
\end_inset

 be the projection map, given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{1}(u,v)=u
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)\in F$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{1}\colon P\to F$
\end_inset

 be the inclusion map, given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{1}(u)=(u,0)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in P$
\end_inset

.
  Now we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective, so let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be a surjective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon P\to N$
\end_inset

 be any other 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is free, it is also projective, and so there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon F\to M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\phi=\psi\circ\pi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon P\to M$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}=\phi\circ\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi\circ\widetilde{\psi} & =\varphi\circ\phi\circ\iota_{1}\\
 & =\psi\circ\pi_{1}\circ\iota_{1}\\
 & =\psi\circ1_{P}\\
 & =\psi.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Projective Modules over Local Ring are Free
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every projective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module is free if and only if every countably generated projective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module is free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a countably generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Suppose any direct summand 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 satisfies the following property: any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is contained in a free direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a countable sequence of generators for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of itself.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in M$
\end_inset

, we see that it is contained in a free direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=F_{1}\oplus M_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Next, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M=F_{1}$
\end_inset

 and we are done, so (by reindexing if necessary) we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\notin F_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{1}$
\end_inset

, and so it is contained in a free direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M & =F_{1}\oplus M_{1}\\
 & =F_{1}\oplus F_{2}\oplus M_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Continuining in this manner, we construct a sequence of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $(F_{n})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}\in F_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\bigoplus_{n=1}^{\infty}F_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(a_{i,j})$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix over a local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i,i}$
\end_inset

 is a unit for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 is a nonunit for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The Leibniz formula for the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det A=\sum_{\sigma\in S_{n}}\mathrm{sgn}(\sigma)\prod_{i=1}^{n}a_{i,\sigma(i)}.
\]

\end_inset

Observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\neq1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=1}^{n}a_{i,\sigma(i)}\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(i)\neq i$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i,\sigma(i)}\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 which implies the product belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 too.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=1}^{n}a_{i,i}\in R\backslash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $R\backslash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is multiplicatively closed.
 Therefore we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A$
\end_inset

 as a unit plus a nontunit.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be a projective module over a local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is contained in a free direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective, it is a direct summand of some free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, say 
\begin_inset Formula $F=P\oplus Q$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P$
\end_inset

 be the element we wish to show is contained in a free direct summand of
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that the number of basis elements needed in the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is minimal, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}e_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\in B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then no 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a linear combination of the other 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{j}=\sum_{i\neq j}a_{i}b_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

, then replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}+b_{i}e_{j}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 and leaving unchanged the other elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, we get a new basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 in terms of which
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}e_{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i\neq j}a_{i}e_{i}+a_{j}e_{j}\\
 & =\sum_{i\neq j}a_{i}e_{i}+\left(\sum_{i\neq j}a_{i}b_{i}\right)e_{j}\\
 & =\sum_{i\neq j}a_{i}(e_{i}+b_{i}e_{j})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

has a shorter expression.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 we decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 into its 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-components, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{i}=y_{i}+z_{i}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}\in Q$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}b_{ij}e_{j}+t_{i}\label{eq:directsummandpandqfree}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 other than 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To finish the proof it suffices to show that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $(b_{ij})$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 For then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\to F$
\end_inset

 sending 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\mapsto y_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

 and fixing 
\begin_inset Formula $B\backslash\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},\dots,y_{n}$
\end_inset

 together with 
\begin_inset Formula $B\backslash\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 form a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then the submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},\dots,y_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a free submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subseteq P$
\end_inset

 and both 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are direct summands of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in N$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}e_{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}y_{i}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a free direct summand of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $(b_{ij})$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 Plugging 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:directsummandpandqfree})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 into
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}e_{i}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}y_{i}
\]

\end_inset

and equating coefficients gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{j}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}b_{ij}.
\]

\end_inset

But as noted above, our choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 guarantees that no 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a linear combination of the other 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is a nonunit for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-b_{ii}$
\end_inset

 is a nonunit, so in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{ii}$
\end_inset

 is a unit for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 But a matrix over a local ring having units along the diagonal and nonunits
 elsewhere is invertible, as its determinant is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a projective module over a local ring, then 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Local Conditions for being Projective
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be a finitely presented 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 The following are equivalent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a projective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-module for all prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

-module for all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, then these statements are also equivalent to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
resume
\end_layout

\end_inset

there is a finite set of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in R$
\end_inset

 that generate the unit ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{a_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{a_{i}}$
\end_inset

-module for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show 1 implies 2.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a projective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 be a maximal ideal.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective, it is a direct summand of a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=P\oplus Q.
\]

\end_inset

Since localization commutes with direct sums, this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\mathfrak{p}}=P_{\mathfrak{p}}\oplus Q_{\mathfrak{p}}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a direct summand of a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-module.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a projective 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-module.
 Since projective modules over local rings are free, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is free.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

That 2 implies 3 is clear, so we just need to show that 3 implies 1.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module for all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective, we need to show that for any surjective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

, then induced 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,\varphi)\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,M)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,N)
\]

\end_inset

 is also surjective, so let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be a surjective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,\varphi)\text{ is surjective} & \iff\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,N)\slash\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,M)\cong0\\
 & \iff(\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,N)\slash\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,M))_{\mathfrak{m}}\cong0\text{ for all maximal ideals }\mathfrak{m}\subseteq R\\
 & \iff\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,N)_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(P,M)_{\mathfrak{m}}\cong0\text{ for all maximal ideals }\mathfrak{m}\subseteq R\\
 & \iff\mathrm{Hom}_{R_{\mathfrak{m}}}(P_{\mathfrak{m}},N_{\mathfrak{m}})\slash\mathrm{Hom}_{R_{\mathfrak{m}}}(P_{\mathfrak{m}},M_{\mathfrak{m}})\cong0\text{ for all maximal ideals }\mathfrak{m}\subseteq R\\
 & \iff\mathrm{Hom}_{R_{\mathfrak{m}}}(P_{\mathfrak{m}},\varphi_{\mathfrak{m}})\text{ is surjective for all maximal ideals }\mathfrak{m}\subseteq R
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last if and only if is true since 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is free (and hence projective) for all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subseteq R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show 4 is equivalent to 1,2, and 3 when 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is finite and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{supp}\,P$
\end_inset

 is finite, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{supp}\,P=\{\mathfrak{p}_{1},\dots,\mathfrak{p}_{m}\}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, statement 2 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}$
\end_inset

 being a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}$
\end_inset

-module for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Projective Dimension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 A 
\series bold
free resolution 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagram}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] & F_{k+1} 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _{k+1}"] & F_k 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots  
\backslash
arrow[r] & F_1 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _1 "] & F_0 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _0 "] & M 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with finitely generated free 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a free resolution has 
\series bold
length 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is minimal with this property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 is a local ring, then a free resolution as above is called 
\series bold
minimal 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{k}(F_{k})\subset\mathfrak{m}F_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

, and then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}(M):=\mbox{rank}(F_{k})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

, is called the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th 
\series bold
Betti number 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 What does the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{k}(F_{k})\subset\mathfrak{m}F_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 have to do with being minimal? Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i}:=\mbox{Ker}(\varphi_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{diagram})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 breaks up into exact sequences of the form 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagram2}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  F_k 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _k " ] & F_{k-1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K_{k-2} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tensoring 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{diagram2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagram3}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  F_k / 
\backslash
mathfrak{m} F_k 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
bar{ 
\backslash
varphi } _k " ] & F_{k-1} / 
\backslash
mathfrak{m} F_{k-1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K_{k-2} / 
\backslash
mathfrak{m} K_{k-2} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{k}(F_{k})\subset\mathfrak{m}F_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{dim}_{A/\mathfrak{m}}(F_{k-1}/\mathfrak{m}F_{k-1})=\mbox{dim}_{A/\mathfrak{m}}(K_{k-2}/\mathfrak{m}K_{k-2})=b_{k-1}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying Nakayama's lemma shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k-1}(M)$
\end_inset

 is the minimal number of generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{k-2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 be a local Noetherian ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a minimal free resolution.
 The rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{k}$
\end_inset

 in a minimal free resolution is independent of the resolution.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a minimal resolution of finite length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & F_{n} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & F_{n-1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots  
\backslash
arrow[r] & F_0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M  
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
