\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is any free resolution, then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{s_{0}}$
\end_inset

 be a minimal set of generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and consider the surjective map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{0}\colon F_{0}:=R^{s_{0}}\to M$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{0}(a_{1},\dots,a_{s_{0}})=\sum_{i=1}^{s_{0}}a_{i}u_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{s_{0}})\in F_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Because of Nakayama's Lemma, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{s_{0}}$
\end_inset

 induces a basis of the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{0}$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}_{0}:F_{0}\slash\mathfrak{m}F_{0}\cong M\slash\mathfrak{m}M$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi_{0}\subset\mathfrak{m}F_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of a finitely generated module over a Noetherian ring, hence
 is finitely generated.
 As before, we can find a surjective map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\colon F_{1}:=R^{s_{1}}\to K_{1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the minimal number of generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing in this manner, we obtain a minimal free resolution for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 To show the invariance of the Betti numbers, we consider two minimal resolution
s of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _{n+1} "] & F_{n} 
\backslash
arrow[r] &  
\backslash
cdots  
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _1 "] & F_0 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _0 "] & M  
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi _{n+1} "] & G_{n} 
\backslash
arrow[r] &  
\backslash
cdots  
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi _1 "] & G_0 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi _0 "] & M  
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{0}\slash\mathfrak{m}F_{0}\cong M/\mathfrak{m}M\cong G_{0}\slash\mathfrak{m}G_{0}
\]

\end_inset

and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{rank}(F_{0})=\mbox{rank}(G_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{1},\dots,f_{s_{0}}\}$
\end_inset

, respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{1},\dots,g_{s_{0}}\}$
\end_inset

 be bases of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}$
\end_inset

, respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\psi_{0}(g_{i})\}$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{0}(f_{i})=\sum_{j}a_{ij}\cdot\psi_{0}(g_{j})
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{ij})$
\end_inset

 defines a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}\colon F_{0}\to G_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{0}\circ\alpha_{1}=\varphi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\alpha}_{1}:F_{0}/\mathfrak{m}F_{0}\to G_{0}/\mathfrak{m}G_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism since it is a composition of isomorpisms: 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\alpha}_{1}=\overline{\psi}_{0}^{-1}\circ\overline{\varphi}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we derive that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(a_{ij})\neq0\mbox{ mod }\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(a_{ij})$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is local ring) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 Especially, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi_{0}\to\ker\psi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

, considered as matrices, have entries in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, and since we have surjections 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}\to\ker\varphi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1}\to\ker\varphi_{0}$
\end_inset

, it follows, as before, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{rank}(F_{1})=\mbox{rank}(G_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can continue like this and obtain the invariance of the Betti numbers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


