\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{dim}\,I=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y-1$
\end_inset

 belongs to a minimal associated prime of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, yet 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{dim}(\langle I,y-1\rangle)=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 also belongs to a minimal associated prime of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{dim}(\langle I,x\rangle)=1$
\end_inset

.
 The difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $y-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 here is that 
\begin_inset Formula $y-1$
\end_inset

 belongs to the minimal associated prime 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x-1,y-1\rangle$
\end_inset

 whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 belongs to the minimal associated prime 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now if we localize at the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle x,y\rangle$
\end_inset

, then the table above transforms as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
